CLINICAL HISTORY:  57 year old woman with epilepsy following intracerebral hemorrhage,
now with increasing right sided weakness and worsening language.  Past history of craniotomy on the right.

MEDICATIONS:  Codeine, Trileptal, Crestor, ASA

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation is performed.  Technically this EEG is remarkable for a great deal of muscle and motion artifact.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is somewhat poorly organized. There is also a great degree of muscle artifact.  Superimposed upon this are bursts of rhythmic and arrhythmic delta activity in the right hemisphere.   The activity from the right frontal region tends to be rhythmic delta activity.  Underlying sharp waves are noted in this sharply contoured record and include T4/C4 and FP2. Features of drowsiness include additional bursts of paroxysmal high amplitude delta with an underlying right frontal sharp wave.	Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR:   84 bpm

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1. 	FIRDA.
2. 	Paroxysmal slowing in the right frontal region.
3.	Sharp waves from the right, many of which are frontal, but some of which are temporal.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are similar to previous study with both a right hemispheric  process and background slowing and disorganization.  This is the first EEG in 1.5 years.  The patient had been relatively seizure free since February 2008.

HISTORY: 74 year old female with new onset generalized tonoclonic seizure less than 45 seconds.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Vancomycin, Valium.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. There was no photic or hyperventilation simulation used.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This is a diffusely slow EEG with an 8 Hz predominant rhythm. There are transient sharps originating from the right occipital region. It does occasionally involve the left occipital region. There is a posterior 3 to 6 Hz dominant focal slowing and sharp waves, sometimes seen With the sharp wave and sometimes independently.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Diffuse disturbance of cerebral function.
2. Exhibital sharp waves are supportive of a localized mechanism for seizures.
CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localized mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old right handed male with occipital headache, nausea, vomiting, confusion, and a past history of stroke.

MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Neurontin.


INTRODUCTION: Digital EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1  channel  of EKG.  Only photic stimulation could be performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is moderately slow with background theta.  There are intermittent shifting asymmetries.  The waking record is less asymmetric and there is, at times, a 7 Hz posterior dominant rhythm, but
in drowsiness the most common asymmetry is disruption of theta frequency activity in the left relevant to the right with faster pattern on the right, but there are shifting asymmetries.

HR:	96 bpm


IMPRESSION: Abnormal  EEG due to:
1. 	Background slowing.
Shifting asymmetry with more disrupted faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.

CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No epileptiform features are observed.  The findings described above may be correlated with this patient's imaging. Toxic metabolic encephalopathy, such as HHNK, can contribute to the generalized slowing, as well as the shifting slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old male with right parietal headache, alcohol cocaine abuse, epilepsy and hypertensive emergency. Past EEG Digitrace EEG evaluation for paroxysmal dizziness.

MEDICATIONS: Haldol, Ativan, ASA, Heparin, Zocor, Hydralazine, Clonidine, Isosorbide, Lasix, ferrous Sulfate, Senna, Amlodipine, Phoslo, Lorazepam

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is primarily drowsy.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In drowsy EEG, the background includes primarily a theta frequency pattern. Despite the artifacts, once again independent right or left anterior temporal sharp waves are identified at one point relatively frequent on the right but clearly bilateral. Features of drowsiness are as described above with an increase in background slowing. Photic stimulation seems to elicit a driving response and unfortunately there is a great deal of artifact in the record:

HR: 60 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Independent, right or left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Despite the problems with the record described above, the sharp waves can clearly be differentiated from artifacts. They are more prominent on the right today, but were previously identified form both right and left.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 50 year old patient who presented to the hospital after multiple episodes of vomiting and unresponsiveness. The patient has a history of diabetes and he presented with hyperglycemia. The EEG was obtained to rule out status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan, Labetalol
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and 1 channel of EKG. There was no hyperventilation or photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly low voltage and is very slow. There are some technical issues with the record in addition to eye movement artifact. There are some frontal sharp waves which are of higher amplitude on the left. Unfortunately, eye movement artifacts also appear higher on the left. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta. Stimulation of patient produces little but more of theta.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Diffusely depressed with possible sharp waves in the left frontal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing could be a post ictal phenomenon or due to the patient's metabolic abnormalities. His medications, the use of Ativan, could also contribute to this pattern. If the patient does not improve a followup study should be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 34 year old right handed female with history of seizures, status postAVM in the left temporal region removed 5 years ago. The patient had been seizure free until December 2008 when she started having break through seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Lamictal.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were both performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm with intermittent left temporal focal slowing. Drowsiness and hyperventilation both accentuates the focal theta from the left temporal region. In hyperventilation the focal slowing is sustained. In drowsiness it is sometimes sharply contoured at 7. Photic stimulation elicits driving.

HR: 66bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left temporal focal slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive sharp waves were identified on this record. The focal slowing is in the region of the AVM resection. If further information Is needed a repeated study is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 82 year old male with gamma knife treatment for meningioma, increasing
seizures with lower limb shaking followed by generalized tonic-clonic activity. Patient' also has a
long history of left foot spasms.
I
Baclofen, Dilantin, Tramadol, Keppra. Zocor, Lisinopril, Januvia, Flomax
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode
placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: There are portions when the patient is maximally awake
where there is a 5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm. Other portions of the record include more of
an arrhythmic delta pattern with triphasic waves. There is shifting slowing, particularly In the
right central and right occipital region with sharp waves in the right occipital region.
HR: 90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Rhythmic background slowing.
2. Arrhythmic delta.
3. Triphasic waves.
4. Focal slowing in the right hemisphere with right central and occipital sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing and the magnitude of the focal slowing is
similar to previous studies. This individual has had 2 prior EEGs for shaking and left leg spasm.
The triphasic waves suggest, and the Increase in background slowing may be due to metabolic
problem or worsening of his primary brain pathology.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 22 year old right handed woman with Down syndrome and
increasing seizures since 2008-2009.

MEDICATIONS: Lamictal, Vimpat.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was
performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes
generous beta. There is excess theta but there is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm. Technically,
this EEG history a great deal of artifact and the tech tries to use the 35 Hz filter, but
there is still a fair amount of artifact noted in the background. This overall slow
background is characterized by increasing theta in drowsiness. Photic stimulation elicits
scant driving.

HR: 90 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess beta.
2. Excess theta.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No slow spike in wave activity nor focal temporal sharp
waves were identified today. This represents an improvement for this individual who
has previously demonstrated prominent epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 63 year old male with frequent episodes of left sided tingling without loss of consciousness.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In maximum wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9 Hz alpha rhythm, but there is a small amount of theta. As the patient becomes drowsy, the theta becomes more prominent. Vertex waves, spindles and posts are observed in stage 2 sleep. Hyperventilation produces a small of slowing. Photic stimulation does not elicit a driving response.
HR: 72bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is mildly abnormal due to:
1. Mild excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. The excess theta described above may be due to this patient's medications.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 66 year old woman with epilepsy and syncopal spells which typically occur in church.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Carbamazepine, ASA
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed In lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9.5 Hertz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of tow voltage, frontal central beta activity. Hyperventilation produces an increase in slowing. Drowsiness is associated with slow rolling eye movements. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
1. Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The excess theta has been described in 2 previous EEGs. No epileptiform features were identified today. At least one of the previous EEGs demonstrated some generalized spike and slow wave activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old woman with a 4 cm posterior fossa hematoma and altered mentation.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Percocet, Protonix
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a slow pattern with a mixture of theta and delta. The overall activity is relatively rhythmic and includes approximately 1 Hz delta, 3.5 Hz delta, and 4.5 Hz activity. In addition, there is some eye movement but there is also a subtle, right frontal sharp wave noted. FIRDA is also observed and is present bilaterally. Stimulation of the patient seems to produce more of a theta pattern than the frontal delta. Vigorous stimulation is not performed.
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to.
1. Replacement of normal background with the pattern of rhythmic slowing.
2. Right frontal sharp waves.
3. Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings may be correlated with imaging and clinical history. This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function in that there are frontal sharp waves, additional recording may be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 43 year old male with multiple medical problems, acutely unresponsive.
MEDICATIONS: Ativan
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is intubated but somewhat responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates marked background slowing with a mixture of delta and theta.
HR: 150 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing, more prominent at the close of the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Clinical correlation given the severity of this patient's neurologic findings is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 70 year old woman with epilepsy since 1984. Black-out spells. Auditory hallucinations.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. This is her fifth EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is an increased 5-Hz posterior dominant rhythm. There is a small amount of excess temporal theta. In hyperventilation, there is subtle focal delta in the temporal regions, right more so than the left. The activity in the temporal regions is sharply contoured bilaterally. Vertex waves and spindles are identified in stage 2 sleep. Subtle right temporal sharp waves are noted in relaxed wakefulness.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Mild excess temporal theta for age.
2. Subtle right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The epileptiform activity identified today is much less prominent than that seen╖ in the 4 previous EEGs. The background otherwise is not significantly changed.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 47 year old right handed male with cocaine related dementia, severe hypertension, heart failure. The patient had a seizure followed by visual impairment and is poorly cooperative. Acute right occipital infarct.

MEDICATIONS: Lasix, Carbamazepine, Furosemide, Hydralazine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is not particularly cooperative. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 6.8 Hz alpha rhythm. The overall background is disorganized with theta frequency activity, bursts of frontally predominant delta activity and some shifting arrhythmic delta activity including some identified in the right posterior quadrant. Independent, right or left anterior temporal sharp waves are observed. Some of these are bilateral, frontotemporal and a few are right central parietal. Stimulation of the patient produces no alerting response. When unstimulated, the patient drifts off to sleep with significantly more delta.

HR: 84 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Independent right or left temporal sharp waves.
3. New sharp waves which are in the right central parietal region.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: The background slowing has been previously described. The independent left or right temporal sharp waves have also been noted before. The right central parietal are new findings. This EEG supports a localization-related mechanism for epilepsy. In that there is an occipital lobe Infarct, the focal features are less prominent than one might anticipate.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 68 year old woman with multiple abdominal pathologies, open abdomen, multiple chest tubes. The patient had an event yesterday with head turning and alteration of awareness. The patient remains intubated, somewhat responsive, eyes now midline, but moving the left arm a bit more sluggishly than the right. Sepsis, unresponsiveness.

MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Vancomycin, Cefepime, Antifungal

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is poorly responsive.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a pattern of rhythmic background theta with shifting arrhythmic delta activity. Intermittently there is a bit more arrhythmic delta activity on the right compared to the left. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in faster state theta frequency activity.

HR: 96 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal features described above are relatively subtle this bedside recording pathology. The presence of reactivity to tactile stimulation is a positive prognostic feature. No epileptiform features were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 66 year old woman status post recent carotid stent placement
with progressive encephalopathy and asterixis. Difficulty finding the right word. Recent
negative MRI for infarct but positive Tox screen.

MEDICATIONS: Levothroid, Hydrochlorothiazide, Diovan, Zocor, ASA, Pantoprazole,
ISOSORBIDE, Metoprolol

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20

system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is awake with
frequent eye blink.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes primarily rhythmic
theta with 5 Hz and 7 Hz activity as well as smaller amounts of delta. Muscle artifact
produces some artifacts. Features of drowsiness include a decrease in eye movements
as well as an increase in delta. There are a handful of triphasic waves noted in the
record which can be differentiated from the patient's eye movements.

HR: 72bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:

1. The presence of rhythmic background theta.
2. Triphasic waves.
3. Generalized slowing
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The features described above are nonspecific but are
relatively characteristic for a metabolic encephalopathy. No significant focal features

were observed and there were no epileptiform features although this is a sharply
contoured record.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 74 year old right handed male with numbness, weakness, difficulty speaking, carotid stenosis.
MEDICATIONS: Aspirin, Diovan, Protonix, Lisinopril
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. There is no hyperventilation. There is no photic simulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there was a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm but there is a scant amount of 6 Hz background activity. In addition, there is intermittent shifting, irregular delta activity seen infrequently in wakefulness from either hemisphere.
HR: 72 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Mild excess theta.
2. Mild background disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. These findings are quite modest for an adult of this age and can be seen in underlying cerebrovascular disease.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old right handed male admitted to the hospital on April 18, 2010 with a left perisylvian Infarct characterized by language difficulty and significant confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Lisinopril, Digoxin, Zocor, Coumadin, Lanoxin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was completed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. There is nearly continuous, rhythmic slowing in the left anterior temporal region. Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta, followed by bilateral frontal slowing. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response at 7 Hz and faster flash frequencies.
HR: 60 bpm with significant EKG artifact.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Left frontal temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The focal slowing is in the region of this patient's recent infarct. This EEG contrasts to a previous EEG in 2006, which was a normal study. That study was performed for an episode of 1 hour of aphasia. No epileptiform features were noted in either EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 59 year old woman, nursing home resident found unresponsive and seizing in the emergency room. History of HIV, diabetes, schizophrenia, hepatitis C and found down seizing 2 days ago.
MEDICATIONS: Unknown.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a continuous pattern, poorly organized with mixture of irregular theta, some beta activity, some alpha frequency activity and delta. There is a suggestion of a 7 hertz posterior dominant rhythm seen on occasion. As the tracing continues, the patient is a bit more agitated with muscle and movement artifact, but when she calms down, it is more of a mixed frequency theta pattern with a suggestion of some underlying delta in the right occipital region.
HR: 90 to 116 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing and disorganization.
2. Right occipital delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No definitive epileptiform features are observed. If additional information is needed, a repeat study in the lab when she is cooperative may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 29 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, rare early
morning or nocturnal tonic clonic seizures typically in the context of sleep deprivation.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG
demonstrates a well developed symmetric reactive 9 hertz alpha rhythm reaching 80
microvolts. Occasional, frontally predominant bursts of high amplitude, 3-5 hertz spike
and slow wave activity are identified in wakefulness. They are accentuated in early
drowsiness and by hyperventilation. Bursts are typically frontally predominant and
symmetrical although there are a handful that demonstrate shifting symmetry and rare
bursts that are occipitally predominant. Photic stimulation elicits driving, but does not
seem to accentuate the spike in wave activity.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Frontally predominant 3-5 hertz spike in wave activity.
2. Occasional spike in wave discharge which may be a little bit more asymmetric or
posteriorly predominant
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings have been identified in this patient's
previous EEGs. They are most supportive of a primary generalized mechanism for
epilepsy, but could be seen in a secondary generalized mechanism.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 75 year old woman with a seizure September 2009,
hypertension, diabetes hypercholesterolemia and ataxia.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, ASA, Insulin, Metformin, Levetiracetam, HCTZ
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation are performed.
This is a 1 hour sleep-deprived EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat
disorganized, but there is a 10 hertz alpha rhythm. There is wicket activity and a small
amount of temporal, shifting slowing. This shifting slowing is more prominent in the left
temporal region with the underlying wicket activity. Features of drowsiness include an
increase in theta, but deeper stages or sleep are not sustained. Photic stimulation elicits
a subtle driving response.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Shifting temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, there were no right
occipital sharp waves identified. There is prominent wicket activity and left temporal
slowing. Because of this, consideration for a more prolonged sleep study would be
helpful to be absolutely certain that there are no left temporal sharp waves.
a subtle driving response.
HR: 80 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
1. Shifting temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, there were no right
occipital sharp waves identified. There is prominent wicket activity and left temporal
slowing. Because of this, consideration for a more prolonged sleep study would be
helpful to be absolutely certain that there are no left temporal sharp waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 49 year old left handed woman with refractory epilepsy, schizophrenia, hypothyroidism.
MEDICATIONS: Topamax, Depakote, Valproic Acid
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is poorly organized with excess background theta. There is focal slowing noted in the background, particularly in the right hemisphere, but there is some shifting and slowing from either hemisphere. Discrete T2 sharp waves can be observed which can be differentiated from EKG artifact. Features of drowsiness include an increase in rhythmicity. In drowsiness, there are a handful of sharp waves observed from the left. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response which demonstrates some shifting asymmetries but is a bit better preserved on the left than the right.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Generalized background slowing.
2. Shifting and slowing with focal features from either hemisphere.
3. Right temporal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: In comparison to previous studies, this pattern with primarily right temporal seizures has been seen in her 7 prior EEGs.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 72 year old woman with left MCA infarct and last previously evaluated in November for left gaze paresis and possible seizures.

MEDICATIONS: Lamictal, Keppra, ASA, Labetalol, Hydralazine, Lorazepam, Pantoprazole, Insulin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is somewhat disorganized. There is an 8 hertz alpha rhythm with a smaller amount of 10 and 11 hertz activity. Shifting arrhythmic delta cavity is identified in the right or left temporal region. It is sharply contoured, but there is no definitive sharp waves. Features of drowsiness include an increase in rhythm followed by vertex waves. Sleep is not sustained. Wicket activity is observed. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. Heart rate is 50 BPM.

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Arrhythmic background delta.
2. Shifting, sharp wave contour and slowing.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: There are no epileptiform features identified in either EEG. This study, however, does not include stage II sleep. This EEG supports a bihemispheric process compatible with a history of cerebral ischemia.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 46 year old right handed male with seizures.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is noted to be very sweaty. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized. There is shifting slowing. In addition, there is arrhythmic delta activity particularly in the left temporal region. In this sharply contoured background, there is a suggestion of a left posterior temporal sharp wave identified in wakefulness. Sharply contoured slowing is also noted at C3fT3. Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:1. A slow and disorganized background.2. Superimposed focal slowing from the left hemisphere. 3. Sharply contoured activity in the left posterior quadrant.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old woman with refractory epilepsy for 1 year, abnormal MRI of the brain. The patient describes episodes with head jerking, loss of consciousness and blackout spells. Also depression, dysphoria and feelings of hopelessness and suspicion.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel if EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation were completed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz posterior dominant rhythm which is sometimes disrupted on the right when compared to the left. Prominent features in the record include intermittent right temporal focal slowing, right anterior temporal spike and still wave or sharp and still wave complexes and a single burst with a burst of left anterior temporal sharp waves. Hyperventilation accentuates the focal right anterior temporal sharp waves. Features of drowsiness include POSTS. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Right temporal lobe sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a localization related mechanism for epilepsy. Correlation with imaging may be important but the primary epileptiform activity in this record is on the right.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 	69 year old woman with metabolic encephalopathy, abdominal pain and seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Ativan, Morphine, Zofran, Heparin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is slow and disorganized with a mixture of rhythmic theta and delta. Stimulation of the patient produces an increase in rhythmic theta activity. Drowsiness was characterized by an increase in arrhythmic delta.
HR:	78 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1.    Background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:   The pattern described above is nonspecific and could be seen in a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy. No epileptiform features were identified today.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old right handed male with epilepsy since age 21. Seizures described as slight episodes of dizziness, shaking a bit of spell without loss of consciousness or falling which last 15 to 20 minutes.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Folate Acid, Ibuprofen, Phenytoin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation was performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized with excess theta and an alpha rhythm of 7 Hz to 8 Hz. Shifting slowing is identified in the posterior regions and occasionally in the right hemisphere. In a transition to sleep, bursts of rhythmic frontal slowing are observed.
HR: 78bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
2. Background slowing.
3. Disorganization.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. The pattern described above may be due to the patient's lifelong epilepsy or to an age related process. If further characterization of the seizures is needed, a more prolonged EEG in the Lab is suggested. Alternatively, comparison with his previous EEGs over the course of decades could provide helpful information.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 64 year old gentlemen admitted on the 13th with acute intracerebral hemorrhage on Coumadin. Hypothermic now with temperature 95.8.

MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Nicardipine, Pantoprazole, Hydralazine, Phenylephrine

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. The data can be re-reviewed with the ECS montage.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is suppressed. There is no change in the background with tactile stimulation. Electrode integrity is confirmed.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Absence of definitive cerebral activity.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: Confirmation of this patient's body temperature is necessary, but at a temperature of 95, this EEG would be satisfactory for an assessment of electrocerebral inactivity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 67 year old ambidextrous woman with refractory seizures right sided shaking, and right facial twitching.

MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Phenobarbital, Keppra, Zoloft, Levothyroxine, Isordil, Lipitor

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is poorly cooperative today.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates almost exclusively muscle and a slow background. There are brief sections where a discernible underlying left anterior temporal sharp wave is noted with a generous field of spread in the left hemisphere. The epileptiform activity is not monomorphic, some of it has more of an anterior spread, mid temporal spread, and it clearly involves even the left parietal region. Epileptiform activity is likely, easily under recognized because of the muscle artifact. At the close of the record there are a few more sharp waves.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG
demonstrates an asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres. The left hemisphere is somewhat slow with an alpha rhythm of 8.3 hertz and a small amount of excess theta to the right hemisphere demonstrates significant disruption of faster frequency activity with scant alpha frequency activity. It is more of a lower voltage featureless delta and theta pattern. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response which is identified bilaterally.
HR: 72bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Continuous focal slowing from the right hemisphere characterized by slower activity and disruption of faster frequency activity.
2. Mild slowing from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings have been noted on 2 previous EEGs. Of note there was a remote history of sharp waves noted on the left which were not seen for this patient today.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 56 year old female with complex partial epilepsy, seizure-free for many years.
MEDICATIONS: Tegretol, Diovan, Starlix, Lipitor, Bystolic, Byetta
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: Throughout much of the record, the patient is in stage I or stage II sleep with vertex waves, POSTS or a pattern of beta with theta. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is drifting off to sleep and does not significantly activate the record. In hyperventilation, there is a suggestion of a left temporal sharp wave and there are a pair of sharp waves in the right temporal region in drowsiness although those have more of the morphology of the a normal variant.
HR: 60bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG abnormal due to:
1. Left temporal sharp waves with a question of a pair of temporal sharp waves on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings may be compared to the patient's previous EEGs from some years ago. They are in agreement with a past history of partial complex epilepsy although epileptiform activity was quite subtle in this record.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old woman with a left meningioma resection, postoperative day 3
with declining mental status. She has significant frontal lobe changes and baseline
encephalomalacia with subdural hemorrhage and confluent intraparenchymal hematomas and
hydrocephalus.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Mannitol, Zofran, Decadron, Pantoprazole, Vancomycin, Cefepime,
Lovenox, Zofran, Dexamethasone
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. The patient is poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is markedly abnormal. The overall
background is a mixture of irregular theta and delta. There are posteriorly predominant sharp
waves, includes P5, and independently T6 02. There are bursts of faster frequency activity
which are picked up at the midline. The activity from the left frontal region is more or less
suppressed and there is more arrhythmic delta activity noted on the right. Tactile stimulation of
the patient seems to elicit a run of epileptiform activity. The epileptiform activity from the right
and left do not seem to be connected, but tactile stimulation seems to have produced
asynchronous train of sharp waves and spikes from either hemisphere, each of which have its
own periodicity. Additional spontaneous bursts of this epileptiform activity are noted. Again,
right occipital temporal and left occipital, again, without clear linkage between the 2 bursts.
96bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Relative suppression of activity from the frontal regions.
2. Occipitally temporal predominant epileptiform activity.
3. Marked background slowing and disorganization.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a highly epileptogenic process. The
epileptiform activity is generous posteriorly, not anteriorly. These findings may be
correlated with this patient's clinical exam and history. The possibility of subclinical seizures
should be considered in this individual.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old woman with bifrontal meningioma, intraparenchymal hemorrhage, markedly abnormal EEG in recent days and poor mental status.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Labetalol, Hydralazine.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is on supplemental nasal cannula oxygen and is responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The EEG demonstrates an awake individual with a defined 7 to 9 hertz alpha rhythm. The alpha rhythm is easier to identify on the right compared to the left. There is also generous faster frequency activity noted in the occipital regions again a bit more than midline and transitioning toward the right central region. Arrhythmic delta activity is noted in the posterior regions. The activity from the frontal regions is low voltage and relatively suppressed. There are a handful of sharply contoured discharges particularly P3. Breach rhythm is noted with some double phase reversing artifact following the craniotomy and this is seen particularly in the left frontocentral region.
HR: 72bpm
IMPRESSION: Improved, but abnormal EEG due to:
1. Relative attenuation of frontal fast cerebral activity.
2. Overall slow background:
3. Asymmetric alpha rhythm.
4. Occasional sharp waves in the left central parietal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: While this remains a very abnormal EEG, it is substantially better, There is now an alpha rhythm present bilaterally, more so on the right than the left. The EEG supports a bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function. No seizures were recorded.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 84 year old woman postoperative day 8, for craniotomy. Nonverbal.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Pantoprazole, Lovenox, Hydralazine, Labetalol, Gentamicin, Dexamethasone, Norvasc, Vancomycin, Cipro, Zofran
INTRODUCTION: digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. The patient is resting comfortably with a Dobhoff tube and recent craniotomy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is abnormal. It is relatively slow particularly in the frontally regions with generous fast activity in the central regions and prominent craniotomy defect. Although there is some head rocking artifact, there are some occasional T6 sharp waves noted in the background. On occasion an alpha rhythm is starting to emerge in wakefulness. Shifting asymmetries are noted in the background.
HR: 84 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background suppression in the frontal regions.
2. Prominent beta activity in the central regions.
3. Shifting arrhythmic delta.
4. A handful of sharp waves in the posterior regions in this case on the right rather than on the left today.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG is considerably improved compared to the first study and is overall essentially unchanged when compared to the second study.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 61 year old male with altered mental status, intermittent paroxysmal spells of tremulousness and tachycardia. Past history of stroke, multiple seizures on the morning of the 4th followed by obtundation.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Seizure and spike detection software is used.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: This long term 24 hour video EEG monitor demonstrates a slow background. The initial sections are primarily delta. As the recording continues, there is more theta frequency noted in the background with 1.5 hertz, 4.2 hertz activity and 6 hertz activity in the background. Stimulation of the patient produces an alerting response with an increase in muscle. Some sections of the record demonstrate medium amplitude FIRDA. Others demonstrate theta. Multiple clinical events are documented by the team. These include impaired mental status. Episodes of tremulousness are noted at 1:56 a.m. and 3:48 a.m. These are not associated with change in awareness. On a handful of occasions, an asymmetry is noted with a 6 hertz alpha rhythm identified on the left, not so clearly identified on the right
HR: 120 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
1. Markedly slow background.
2. Frontal intermittent and rhythmic delta activity.
3. On occasion, an asymmetric alpha rhythm, present only on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are compatible with a generalized disturbance of cerebral function. This is a nonspecific finding and can be seen in the toxic or metabolic encephalopathy as well as other causes. There are no epileptiform features noted. Although a Holter devise was not utilized, the patient has persistent tachycardia rather than intermittent paroxysmal tachycardia.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 85 year old right handed male with 2 seizures for which he is amnestic. Multiple comorbidities. The patient reported to the technologist that he was taking Keppra, but to his physician that he is not.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Lipitor
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation was not possible, but photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is quite well organized for an adult of this age. There is an alpha rhythm, 8.3 to 8. 7 Hz, higher amplitude on the left than the right with some slight asymmetries in terms of the frequency of the alpha comparing the right to the left. Vertex waves are noted in stage I sleep. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 50 bpm.
IMPRESSION: Very minimally abnormal EEG due to:
1. Slight asymmetry of the alpha rhythm and scant slowing of the alpha rhythm for age.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are identified. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested. In view of the magnitude of his previous cerebrovascular disease, the epileptiform features described above are quite subtle.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 68 year old right handed female with complex partial epilepsy, seizure free for many years.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Amlodipine, ASA
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG includes a 9.7 Hz alpha rhythm, which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening. There is a very subtle asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity in the right frontal temporal region. In addition, as the patient becomes drowsy there is more clear rhythmic slowing in the right frontal temporal region and a single sharp wave. Hyperventilation subtly accentuates the focal features. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving. Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.
HR: 66bpm
IMPRESSION: Mild abnormal EEG due to:
1. Subtle, slowing from the right frontal temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a structural or functional process in the right. No sharp waves were identified. This is one of many EEGs for this patient.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 55 year old male with squamous cell carcinoma, stage IV, status post whole brain irradiation for CNS metastasis now with agitation and encephalopathy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote, Dexamethasone
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. The patient is quite dull appearing. The EEG waxes between a lethargic state with occasional arousals.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes a mixture of rhythmic theta and delta. With arousals, there is faster beta frequency activity and some alpha frequency activity. On rare occasions, there is a suggestion of a alpha rhythm.
There are a handful of triphasic waves and poorly formed occasional periodic complexes noted in either hemisphere in the frontocentral regions.
HR: 112 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Marked background slowing.
2. Shifting slowing.
3. Occasional triphasic waves.
4. Occasional poorly formed periodic complexes.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG supports a severe disturbance o cerebral function effecting both hemispheres. No seizures were recorded and there were no prominent epileptiform features.

EEG REPORT
CLINICAL HISTORY: 41 year old right handed woman with episodes lasting 10-15 minutes with eyes rolling back in head, head turning to the left, confusion, seizure versus nonepileptic seizure.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra, Phenytoin.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: As the tracing begins, the background EEG is somewhat abnormal. There is excess theta. There are bursts of slowing. Right frontal temporal sharp waves are noted. There is also some shifting slowing. As the patient becomes drowsy, the asymmetry is a bit more remarkable with focal slowing in the right anterior temporal region and higher amplitude right anterior temporal spike and slow wave complexes. Bursts of sharp waves are noted as the patient transitions into sleep, which are seen first on the right and then on the left. The patient starts to transition into stage sleep. Sharp waves at that point are seen with an unusual field of spread, F8, T4, and then frontal left or right, or with an asymmetry, but with some bilateral representation. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Abundant epileptiform activity with more than 1 localization.
2. Right anterior temporal sharp waves.
3. Sharply contoured delta from the left mid temporal region.
4. Some bifrontal sharp activity.
CLINICAL This EEG supports a focal mechanism for epilepsy. The
background slowing and the focal slowing may be correlated with imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 68 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, increasingly refractory
after this past year; last seizure 1 week ago.
MEDICATIONS: Albuterol, Metoprolol, Keppra, Glipizide, Risperdal, Trazodone,
ASA, Levetiracetam, Pantoprazole, Polyethylene, Simvastatin, Hyoscyamine, Oxycodone,
Bisacodyl
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of
electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Photic stimulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG demonstrates a marked asymmetry
between the 2 hemispheres. The right hemisphere demonstrates disruption of the alpha rhythm
with arrhythmic delta activity and high-amplitude right posterior temporal spikes and sharp
waves. Not all the sharp waves in the right hemisphere are identical. On some occasions,
there seems to be a positivity at C4 with a T6 phase reversal. The field is spread and overall
amplitude is somewhat variable. In addition, the amount of arrhythmic delta activity in the right
hemisphere is also variable. This high-amplitude spike demonstrates significant spread in a
referential montage and actually has picked up T6, 02, T 4, and even L1. On occasion, again
there is a positivity, either T4 or C4, depending on the montage employed and the delta is
throughout the right hemisphere. The left hemisphere is relatively well organized with a 9 Hz
posterior dominant rhythm. Features of drowsiness include accentuation of the epileptiform
activity and arrhythmic delta. Photic stimulation does not activate the record.
HR: 72 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Nearly continuous focal slowing from the right hemisphere.
2. High amplitude right occipital and posterior temporal spiking.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: The prominent epileptiform activity as well as the focal slowing
has been seen in previous studies for this individual. This EEG demonstrates significant
epileptogenicity, even when she is well.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 72 year old woman with aphasia, change in mental status, MCA
infarct, dementia, panic, other medical problems.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin, Zyprexa, Risperdal, Fibercon, Furosemide. Motrin,
Acidophilus
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic stimulation was
performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG is a high amplitude,
disorganized, somewhat chaotic-appearing record. There is a great deal of muscle
movement artifact. There are sharp waves at noted F7 and at T4. There is also some
focal slowing and more significant sharp waves in the right mid and anterior temporal
region. Muscle artifact is problematic in the frontal regions. The overall background is
slow. Photic stimulation does not activate record.
HR: 96 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. Background slowing.
2. Absence of the normal morphologies for an adult of this age.
3. Sharp waves primarily right mid temporal but sometimes left anterior temporal.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: These findings are similar to the study done the previous
day. There is no quite as much in the way of epileptiform activity. If epilepsy is an
important consideration, a consideration for a longer term recording to capture her
events is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed gentleman with history of atrial fibrillation, multiple bilateral infarcts including right MCA left frontal, status post tonic/clonic seizure for the last 11 months.  Last seizure was 48 hours ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Pradaxa, Simvastatin, Lisinopril, Metoprolol, Protonix, Glyburide, Miralax
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  There is no hyperventilation nor photic stimulation performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background EEG includes an 11 Hz alpha rhythms with some 9 Hz activity as well.  There is a subtle asymmetry.  The alpha rhythm is sometimes disrupted on the right compared to the left.  The alpha rhythm drops out on the right earlier than the left.  There is occasional, excess theta noted from either hemisphere, and the activity is overall a little higher amplitude on the left compared to the right.  Features of stage I sleep include vertex waves.
HR:    60 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Modest background disorganization for age.
Disruption of the alpha rhythm on the right compared to the left.
An amplitude asymmetry with a higher amplitude pattern on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features.  There are bi-hemispheric changes, which may be correlated with neuro-imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old right handed woman with history of epilepsy who stopped taking her medication now presents for recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Mirtazapine, Lisinopril, Hydrochlorothiazide, Oxcarbazepine, Naproxen.
REASON FOR EEG:  History of seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with anterior temporal and EKG electrodes. Wakefulness and sleep was recorded. Activating procedures with photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 Hz with low amplitude 20-60 microvolts, which is reactive to eye opening. There is normal central beta. Sleep, stage 1 architecture is seen. Activating procedures, including photic stimulation and hyperventilation does not reveal abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen independently at F7/T3 and F8/T4 frequently at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts. Some of the discharges, specifically the ones on the right, have a suspiciously sharp contour but are not clearly epileptiform.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
independent bilateral anterior temporal focal slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of independent bilateral anterior temporal cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology. No seizures nor epileptiform discharges were seen. Please note, that more prolonged recording may aid in eliciting epileptiform discharges.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  96 year old male found hypothermic this morning with C1-C2 fracture, intubated, comatose, status post prolonged code.
MEDICATIONS:  Atropine, EPI
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is stimulated vigorously during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This EEG is remarkable for essentially a suppressed pattern.  There is EKG and muscle artifact, but no definitive cerebral activity.
HR:   Irregular 60 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Absence of definitive cerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This may well be a hyperacute study.  These findings should be placed in their appropriate clinical context.  Additional neurodiagnostic information may be of value in decision making process.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   32 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, currently seven months pregnant with nocturnal seizures.  Now with a one-month history of blackout spells.  She tells the tech that she is amnestic for what she does during the blackout spells.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Keppra
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz, 30 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of focal, frontocentral beta.  Drowsiness is characterized by slowing of the alpha rhythm followed by an increase in beta and then vertex waves.  Vertex waves, K complexes and spindles are observed in stage II sleep.
The patient is asleep during photic stimulation; in fact, she is in stage II sleep.  In the sleep state, there are a handful of vertex waves which phase reverts to the right of the midline.  Others are symmetric at the midline. There is a single vertex wave which phase reverses to the left of the midline.
HR:    90 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Very mildly abnormal EEG due to:
Vertex waves which phase reverse to the right of the midline.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a nonspecific finding.  It is not definitively epileptogenic or epileptiform.  In addition, the minor asymmetry described above can be artifactual.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  24 year old right handed female with history of seizures since age 6, now with recurrent seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Levetiracetam
REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement with additional anterior temporal and single lead electrode.  Wakefulness and sleep are recorded.  Activating procedures of hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that is mainly in the 9-10 Hz; at times it is faster, but is reactive to eye opening and eye closing.  There is normal frontal central beta.  Sleep is characterized by stage I.  Activating procedures with no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen at T3 and independently and T4 at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
bilateral mid temporal focal slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with bilateral anterior temporal focal slow waves, which is nonspecific with regard to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  22 year old left handed female, agenesis of the corpus callosum, epilepsy, now essentially seizure free, asthma, depression, behavioral disorder.  The patient is left handed.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Ursodiol, Vitamin D.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage, 9 Hz alpha rhythm identified, a bit more prominently on the right than the left.  The overall activity is quite low voltage for a young adult, particularly in the frontal regions and particularly in the left frontal region. Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.  Features of drowsiness include rhythmic slowing.  In addition, there is some theta, a bit more prominent in the left central region than the right.  There is a bit of arrhythmic slowing in the transition with breech stage 2 sleep. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  The driving response includes supraharmonic driving, which is present bilaterally.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
An abnormal background with paucity of faster frequency activity in the frontal regions.
Disrupted alpha on the left.
An asymmetry with more disruption of the faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  This EEG may be compared with this individual's childhood studies.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  56 year old male transferred from Episcopal with a stroke characterized by right-sided weakness with repetitive speech.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was not possible but photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9-Hz alpha rhythm.  Wicket activity is noted.  There is subtle, underlying arrhythmic delta activity in the right mid temporal region.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing with POSTS.  Vertex waves and spindles are noted.  In sleep, the focal features are less prominent. Photic stimulation elicits a bilateral driving response but it is a bit more vigorous on the right.  The patient is falling asleep during photic stimulation.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing in the left hemisphere particularly left central temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features noted.  The focal slowing and asymmetric driving response may be correlated with  structural abnormalities in this individual with a stroke.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  71 year old male with pancreatic cancer, Parkinson disease, and declining mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol, Sinemet, Ciprofloxacin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is described as very uncooperative and will not allow the tech to obtain the appropriate impedances.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This bedside EEG demonstrates a pattern with generous beta and theta.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in beta and a drop out of the muscle artifact as well as slow rolling eye movements.  Snore artifact is noted.
HR:    160 bpm and irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess beta.
Excess theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features noted.  There were no specific hallmarks of any sort of encephalopathy.  If additional evaluation is needed, please contact the lab when the patient is more cooperative.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  42 year old right handed woman with tonic clonic seizures, last seizure 3 months ago. Seizures are characterized by incontinence and postictal confusion. Past history: Depression, possible dementia.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Klonopin, Zyprexa, Advair
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is somewhat slow and disorganized. There is prominent 3-4 Hz activity on the left. The right hemisphere has more of a predominance of 4-5 Hz activity, but some of the same 2-3 Hz activity noted on the left. There is a glimpse of an alpha rhythm. Brief drowsiness is characterized by a decrease in eye movements and increase in rhythmicity of the background. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response although there is a fair amount of artifact noted in the background.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
An asymmetry with slower activity on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted. The pattern described above is a nonspecific pattern and can be seen in a diffuse disturbance due
to many different causes. Consideration for a diffuse disturbance and/or a focal process is appropriate in that the left is a bit slower.

HISTORY: 42 year old man with sudden unconsciousness, found to be in PA code,
shocked In the fetal x 2 to 3 times, having a second PA code later for about 13 minutes; now
with no reflexes on exam.
MEDICATIONS: Norepinephrine, Dopamine, Bitartrate
REASON FOR STUDY: Brain death.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video E.EEG was performed at bedside using the brain death protocol
in addition to the 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and
EKG electrodes. During the recording, all electrodes were tested and the recording was
performed at 2 microvolts per mm. The patient was also stimulated during the recording.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES: None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The record reveals an absence of any normal cerebral
electrical activity with an overriding EKG electrode artifact. No normal posterior dominant
rhythm, frontocentral beta, or normal sleep architecture is seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES: Absence of normal cerebral activity, low voltage recording even
at 2 microvolts per mL. Using the double-distance electrodes and 2 microvolts, no electrical
activity can be seen.
SEIZURES: None.
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
1. absence of normal electrocerebral activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: This EEG reveals absence of electrocerebral activity, which in the
right setting, considering the absence of confounding medications or metabolic abnormalities,
with brain death. No seizures or epileptiform activity were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  48 year old  gentleman with renal failure, on dialysis as well as retroviral therapy admitted with right temporal cortical hemorrhage.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  It is at times nearly a discontinuous pattern with bursts of paroxysmal high amplitude theta frequency activity.  These are followed by brief attenuations lasting 1-3 seconds with lower voltage arrhythmic delta activity.  The EEG is more suppressed in the right hemisphere in comparison to the left.  The parasagittal regions are relatively symmetric.
Features noted when the patient is unstimulated include bursts of FIRDA.  There is also some posterior delta noted.  Wakefulness is characterized by eye movement.

IMPRESSION:  Markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Discontinuous pattern.
An asymmetry with a more discontinuous pattern on the right.
Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
Sharply contoured activity in the posterior regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a severe bihemispheric disturbance of cerebral function.  No seizures were recorded.  If indicated, a follow-up study may be of use.

INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is not intubated.

The right hemisphere typically demonstrates more arrhythmic delta activity on the right with periods of bursts with frontally predominantly delta, rare T6 sharp waves.  There are focal features with disruption of faster frequency activity on the right.  There is also bursts of frontal delta.

T6 sharp waves.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old female, status post cardiac arrest on January 7th.  The patient had a tonic-clonic seizure in the CT scan and received 12 mg of Ativan.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Fentanyl, Clindamycin, Demerol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow.  Relatively low voltage.  It includes slow featureless delta and some more scant rhythmic theta with a few bursts of more paroxysmal rhythmic low voltage theta.  In addition, there is a periodic transient noted in the right posterior quadrant.  Sometimes this appears as a pled, other times as slow delta.  It starts at P4 and ends at O2.  It is sometimes spikier at O2 than it is at P2, but occurs first at P4.  As the recording continues, this abnormality is less prominent and appears as an infrequent, periodic delta burst. Stimulation of the patient clearly produces a reactivity with an increase in faster frequency activity.
HR:    104 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Marked background slowing.
A slow, periodic complex in the right occipital or parietal region which improves over time.
Right posterior focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates both positive and negative prognostic features for an individual 3 days post cardiac arrest.  In addition, it is not known when the patient had the seizure.  The overall pattern is one of some improvement in terms of the epileptiform activity over time suggesting that the seizure may have occurred today.  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function as well as a focal disturbance in the right occipital region, but the presence of reactivity and variability are positive prognostic features after cardiac arrest.

96 to 100 bpm

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old woman presents status post V-tach code for 15 minutes and an episode of pain then loss of consciousness and had the code, then noted to have generalized tonic/clonic activity on the CT scan that stabilized and seized again followed by 12 mg of Ativan.  EEG to follow up due to eye movements during neuro exam post-suction.
MEDICATIONS:  Albuterol, Hydralazine, Metoprolol, Lovenox, Pantoprazole, Phenytoin.
REASON FOR STUDY:  History of seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  No activating procedures were performed, although noxious stimulation was administered.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background that, at best, reaches 6 Hz.  During the recording, there was noxious stimuli performed to the patient which would increase the frequency of the recording for about 2 to 3 seconds after stimuli.  No normal sleep architecture is seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at P4 and T6 occasionally throughout the recording.  At times the field appears to be large and appears to spread somewhat to the posterior side to the left occipital region, but mainly all the sharp waves remain in that right posterior quadrant.
Generalized slow waves at 2 to 4 Hz, seen continuously throughout the recording.  In addition, there are episodes of diffuse attenuation seen while the patient is awake.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Focal sharp waves in the right posterior quadrant.
Generalized slow waves with intermittent periods of attenuation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with diffuse cortical dysfunction and injury, which is consistent with the known hypoxic injury.  In addition, there is evidence of right posterior quadrant irritability which has a high likelihood of seizures arising from that region.  No seizures wee seen during the recording.  Lastly, during the stimulation the patient's frequency appeared to improve, which suggests a somewhat more favorable prognosis.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  30 year old right handed male with history of gunshot wound to the head and seizures until 2006, presents status post cranioplasty on January 19, had a witnessed seizure with the head turned to the left, eyes deviated for 1 minute. REASON FOR EEG:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  No activating procedures were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm of 10, which is better seen over the left hemisphere which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is a normal amount of frontocentral beta, except there is a slight asymmetry in the amplitude of the beta which appears to be most decreased over the right hemisphere.  Some normal patterns of stage 1 sleep were seen.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen continuously over the right hemisphere maximally over the parietal (P4) region at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  There also appears to be a decrease in the amplitude of the faster frequencies over this region.
Focal slow waves seen at T3 intermittently at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 mV.  Two of these patterns had a slightly sharply contoured appearance, but did not appear to be clearly pathologic or epileptiform.
SEIZURES:    None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Right hemisphere focal slow waves maximal in the parietal region with additional decreased amplitude in the faster frequencies.
Focal slow waves intermittently seen in the left midtemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the right hemisphere, maximal in the parietal region which is consistent with the known injury and lesion in that region.  In addition, there is evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left midtemporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen

CLINICAL HISTORY:  22 year old right handed woman with absence epilepsy since age 7, previously treated with Zarontin, but she recently stopped her medications.

In the beginning of the EEG, there is a subtle asymmetry.  There seems to be a disruption of faster frequency activity in the right frontal region.  In addition, there is some sharply contoured activity in the left frontocentral region.  In this somewhat sharply contoured background, there seems to be a very subtle underlying sharp wave which can be seen at T3/T5 and C3.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  43 year old right handed female with asthma, bipolar, and history of seizures, that presents with rapidly progressing dementia, now with spontaneous jerks of the upper extremities.
MEDICATIONS:  Lisinopril, Haldol, Lorazepam, Lovenox
REASON FOR STUDY:  Myoclonus and rapidly progressive dementia, concern for seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded while lethargic and confused.  Photic stimulation was performed and no hyperventilation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record to opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz, which is not seen consistently throughout the recording.  There is faster frequencies intermixed into a diffusely slow background of 2-4 Hz, that at times appears to be periodic in nature with frontally sharply contoured waves occurring at 2 Hz, which at times becomes more and more rhythmic.  In between this there is episodes of jerking with associated EMG artifact or muscle artifact in the EMG and only one appears to have a preceding anterior predominant sharp wave.  At times there is intermittent also anterior sharp waves.  No normal sleep is seen. Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:   As above.
SEIZURES:   None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slowing.
Periodic frontally dominant slowing intermixed with faster frequencies.
Frontal sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of a diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  However, the almost or pseudoperiodic pattern of the slowing, in addition to some jerks in clinical myoclonus could be consistent with a rapidly evolving neurogenic disease, like Creutzfeldt-Jakob.  Other causes cannot be excluded as the background at times appears to be faster and less suppressed than what would be expected in a late stage progressive dementia, like Creutzfeldt-Jakob.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 9 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontal central beta seen.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal sharp waves seen at F7/T1 rarely.
Focal slow waves seen at F7/T1 frequently throughout the recording at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-80 mV.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left anterior temporal sharp waves and slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of left anterior temporal dysfunction and irritability, which is consistent with a known stroke in that region.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  69 year old male with lightheadedness, started on Dilantin January. Recurrent syncope in February, follow-up EEG.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, ASA
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz rhythm.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity.  The overall EEG is sharply contoured and there is wicket and mu noted. Following hyperventilation, there is a small amount of shifting slowing particularly in the left temporal region.  Although there is some artifact T4 and F8 electrodes, in drowsiness, there is rare, left central focal slowing with isolated theta or delta waves.  Photic stimulation is remarkable for significant electrode artifact, but bilateral driving.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Occasional, left central slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features seen.  The focal occasional left temporal slowing was noted on a previous EEG, but is a little less remarkable today.  Neither EEG captured extensive sleep.  If seizures are an important
consideration, a repeat tracing with sleep is suggested.  Thus far, this patient has had 2 EEGs, neither of which have demonstrated epileptiform activity.
