CLINICAL HISTORY:  32 year old right handed woman coming in with new-onset seizure and diagnosed with a right brain tumor for 3 years.  The patient has had a seizure during sleep, tonic-clonic, lasting for 1-2 minutes with no recall of events.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax, Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and stage I and II of sleep.
Activating procedures including photic stimulation and hyperventilation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens with well-defined posterior dominant rhythm 9-12 Hz bilaterally which is reactive to eye opening.  There was a shifting and slowing throughout the EKG pattern more on the right than the left.
There is excessive amount of beta waves on the central leads on the right indicative of a breach  rhythm on that side.  The patient appears to go into stage I and II of sleep.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Shifting and slowing more on the right side than the left.
Breach rhythm on the right side.
Occasional C4 sharp waves.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
Shifting and slowing on the right side more than the left.
Breach rhythm on the right side.
Intermittent C4 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to shifting and slowing more on the right than the left with a breach rhythm indicating focal structural brain lesion consistent with a right-sided brain tumor.  Occasional C4 sharp waves could indicate epileptiform potential

CLINICAL HISTORY:  59 year old right handed male with history of seizures, hypertension, CHF, and right sided weakness, as well as headache and confusion was on Dilantin at home.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Hydralazine, Lovenox, Famotidine, ASA.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Headache and confusion.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures, including photic stimulation, was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz with some normal frontal central beta seen.  The patient appears to go into stage I and stage II sleep. Activating procedure, which was photic stimulation, produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Very frequent, almost continuous, focal slowing present at T3 at 2-4 Hz and 20-70 mV.  At one time there is 2 sharply contoured transients in this region, but not clearly epileptiform.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Left mid temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  43 year old right handed female with a history of seizures, asthma, and drug abuse, presents with decreased mental status when she fell down stairs 2 weeks ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Seroquel, Valium, Dilantin, Albuterol, Prilosec.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Change in mental status.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  There is marked muscle movement artifact throughout the recording as the patient would not lie still.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no normal posterior dominant rhythm and no normal frontocentral beta.  The patient does not exhibit any normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  There are generalized slow waves seen in a, at times, pseudoperiodic pattern that is between 2 to 3 Hz with an amplitude of 20 to 60 microvolts, which is seen almost continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized slow waves, at times with a pseudoperiodic pattern.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regard to etiology; however, this pseudoperiodic pattern can be seen with neurodegenerative diseases.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  26 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, seizure free since 2008, 2007 EEG demonstrates a 3.5 spike and wave activity.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, Zonisamide.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with symmetric reactive 10 Hz alpha rhythm and a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  In relaxed wakefulness, prior to hyperventilation, there are bursts of high amplitude, frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity, which are relatively symmetric.  The discharges are less than 2 seconds and start with a 5 Hz discharge transitioning more to a 3 Hz over time.  The bursts are so brief and they are not associated with impairment of awareness.  The technologist gives the patient tasks to do and she is able to count during these brief bursts which wax and wan.
Hyperventilation accentuates the bursts of frontally predominant spike and slow wave activity.  As the patient becomes drowsy, there is a more of a polyspike component to the bursts.
Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  It does not accentuate the epileptiform activity.  The epileptiform activity does occur around the time of stimulation, but it also occurs even just prior to her following the stimulation.
HR:    96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Bursts of high amplitude frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These bursts are quite prominent.  None were longer than 2 seconds in duration and none were associated with impairment of awareness.  The
technologist did extensive testing of the patient to try and see if there would be a pause during the bursts, but she was not able to demonstrate any impairment of awareness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  64 year old woman with CKD, hypertension, anemia, hyperlipidemia and diabetes with 1 week of full body twitching.
MEDICATIONS:  None reported
REASON FOR STUDY:  Patient with body twitching.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video  EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal, single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 9 Hz which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is an increased amount of beta frequency seen diffusely throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow waves seen at F7/T3 and F8/T4 independently throughout the recording at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts.  At times, there are some sharply contoured waveforms in the left temporal region which are more consistent with wickets, not clearly epileptiform.
At times during wakefulness, there appears to be excessive theta seen throughout the recording at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Independent bilateral anterior temporal slowing.
Mild excessive theta in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the bilateral anterior temporal region as well as mild diffuse cerebral dysfunction, both of which are nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  36 year old female with history of seizures, presents with multiple seizures and postictal confusion.
MEDICATIONS:  Vimpat, Topamax, Neurontin, Percocet.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness, but mainly in sleep.  Activating procedures including photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background, however, there are short episodes of wakefulness where for very short periods there appears to be a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz that appears somewhat reactive to eye opening.  Otherwise, the patient, even while awake there appears to be some diffuse slowing and quickly drowses off to stage 1/stage 2 sleep.  There is some normal frontocentral beta seen in the short wakeful state.  Photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Generalized slow waves at 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts which is seen almost continuously throughout the recording and then quickly the patient goes into sleep.
There are some focal sharply contoured waveforms at F8/T4 seen on rare occasions.  Two of them had a clear morphology of BETS, however, one of them had a much higher amplitude and was suspicious for epileptiform activity.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
1.  Generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures were seen.  Please note that the single sharp epileptiform transient was only seen once and it is not clear if it is pathologic.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   29 year old male with mental retardation and cerebral palsy, admitted with Dilantin toxicity and change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Lovenox, Protonix, Heparin
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The EEG is poorly organized.  There is a mixture of frontal beta and background theta.  There is little in the way of a well defined alpha rhythm.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess beta.
Background slowing.
Paucity of normal awake wave forms.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified.  The profound Dilantin toxicity may play a role in the background slowing.  It may be appropriate to repeat an EEG when his level is back in range.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  29 year old right handed male who had a gunshot wound to the head, and brain injury 1 year ago, now with memory difficulties and epilepsy, seizure 2 weeks ago with potential confusion, residual metallic projectile.
MEDICATIONS:  Topamax and Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.  The patient is noted to have had a recent cranioplasty.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  Subtle, focal slowing is noted in the right hemisphere in the central and temporal regions.  Breach rhythm is identified on the right which includes accentuation of faster frequency activity.  There are a handful of simple sharp waves out of the breach rhythm, but done with after going slow waves. Photic stimulation elicits vigorous driving response, but it is a little bit better represented on the left, though it is a bit higher amplitude on the right.
HR:    90 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent, subtle focal slowing from the right hemisphere.
A handful of sharp waves on the right, one or two of which are slow enough to
represent true sharp waves rather than wicket activity in the region of a breach.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is consistent with focal lesion on the right with epileptiform potential.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   65 year old gentleman with a history of epilepsy as well as cardiac disease, unrestrained driver, status post rib fractures and hip dislocation.  Patient reports that he has been seizure free for a year.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Morphine, Insulin, Lovenox, Midazolam, Fentanyl
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Patient is awake.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is disorganized with a 7.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  Occasional bursts of FIRDA are noted.  There is also shifting slowing noted in either hemisphere. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing.
HR:    84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Slow alpha.
Shifting slowing.
Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function which may be acute or chronic in nature.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  60 year old left handed woman, presents with falls with no seizure activity, but similar episodes in the past with some altered mental status and confusion.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 8 Hz which appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is some normal frontocentral beta seen.  The patient appears to go into drowsiness, stage 1 sleep.  Activating procedures which included photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves at 5-7 Hz with an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts seen continuously throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Mild generalized slow waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  68 year old female with history of seizures, apnea, GERD, and frequent episodes of feeling anxious.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol, Topamax, Alendronate, Lovastatin.

The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were performed, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta. Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, reveal no abnormal discharges.  Normal sleep, stage I and stage II, were seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen at T3 with a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-70 mV.  These discharges were seen occasionally.

IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Occasional left mid temporal slowing.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  84 year old right handed gentleman with a seizure in November 2011 and then a second in March 2012.  Both of them were seizures out of sleep.  He was hospitalized at Mercer Hospital in West Philadelphia.  He feels like he has not quite returned to himself.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  The alpha rhythm tends to be slightly asymmetric, little faster on the right than the left, ranging from 8.3 to 8.7.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in theta.  The record is slightly slower on the left posterior region than the right as the patient drifts off to sleep.  Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record, although the slight asymmetry in the alpha rhythm was noted.
HR:    60 bpm, somewhat irregular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
An asymmetry in the alpha rhythm with a somewhat slower pattern on the left.
Occasional, subtle underlying slowing on the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to a previous EEG performed on November 9, 2011 that EEG demonstrated a more focal driving response on the left at 6 Hz compared to the right which was a nonspecific finding.  This EEG does not demonstrate that phenomenon a little slowing on the left.   These findings may reflect the patient's underlying cerebrovascular disease with a past history of silent cerebellar infarct picked up on imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  58 year old male with mitral valve repair on April 13th, required recurrent surgery on April 18th.  Episode of unresponsiveness lasting 15 minutes on the morning of the 23rd.  The patient returned to baseline after 1 hour.
MEDICATIONS:  Lasix, Zosyn
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF RECORD:  The background EEG is somewhat slow, with primarily 7-8 Hz theta frequency pattern.  When the patient arouses, there seems to be a better defined posterior dominant rhythm, sometimes reaching 9 Hz on the left, somewhat attenuated on the right.  This is a relatively somnolent patient, but as he seems to drift off the sleep there is again, although more slowing in the right posterior quadrant.
HR:    144 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing.
Superimposed focal slowing with a slight asymmetry on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There are no epileptiform features identified.  The diffuse slowing is a nonspecific finding, which can be seen in a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.  The focal features may be correlated with imaging.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   49 year old right handed male with past history of stroke, epilepsy.  Seizures usually occur after alcohol consumption.  All seizures occur at 4:30 in the morning.  Past history of bilateral infarcts, right MCA, left frontal, bilateral superior cerebellar.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Simvastatin, Pradaxa, Lisinopril, Metoprolol, Protonix, Glyburide
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG today is reasonably well organized.  There is an 11 Hz alpha rhythm identified on the left, but it a bit slower on the right.  There is a subtle disruption of faster frequency activity on the right, relative to the left. As the patient becomes drowsy, the asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres becomes a bit more prominent with more of a drop out of faster frequency activity on the right than the left and some lower voltage slowing.  Spindles are noted in stage II sleep. Photic stimulation is performed as the patient is drifting off to sleep.  A scant driving response is seen.
HR:    72 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Slowing in the right hemisphere characterized by disruption of the alpha rhythm, intermittent disruption of faster frequency activity and some underlying theta delta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is significantly improved from his previous study on October 10, 2011.  The organization on the left hemisphere is now relatively normal.  No epileptiform features were seen in either of the two EEGs.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  19 year old female with learning disability, asthma, ADHD and behavioral issues, admitted after an altercation with the police, now with opsoclonus and delirium.
MEDICATIONS:  Benadryl.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  This was an awake EEG and uncooperative patient.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In this markedly limited record, the interpretable sections of the record demonstrate a slow background with primarily a theta frequency pattern.  The patient's movement artifact is so remarkable that even the EKG lead is uninterpretable.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Slow theta pattern for an awake adult.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  If additional evaluation is needed, a follow-up study perhaps using a short-acting benzodiazepine is suggested.  These findings were discussed with the clinical team.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  85 year old male with left frontoparietal tumor, atrial fibrillation, cerebral edema, cerebral herniation, progressive somnolence and loss of speech.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Protonix, Labetalol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient is quite drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG demonstrates primarily a rhythmic, 6.5 Hz theta frequency pattern.  There is significant lateral rectus spike artifact picked up on the left.  There is also some subtle focal slowing with some underlying slower delta picked up at T1, T3, T5.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, there is a bit more sharply contoured theta in the left frontotemporal region.
HR:    90 bpm and irregular
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Intermittent, subtle asymmetry primarily in the left midtemporal region.
A handful of very subtle, low amplitude F7 sharp waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In this individual with a focal process on the left, the overall appearance of the EEG is primarily one of more of a generalized process.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  36 year old woman with multiple sclerosis and epilepsy, admitted with recurrent tonic-clonic seizures and postictal confusion, initial presentation in status epilepticus requiring Dilantin load.  Seizures characterized by head turning to the right, then left arm shaking which progresses into a tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Vimpat, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  The patient is somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This EEG demonstrates a slow pattern, rich in beta.  Frequent eye blink artifact is noted.  A discrete sharp wave is noted in the right temporal region.  It has a variable field and can include T2 and T4.
HR:    96 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Excess beta.
Excess delta, particularly frontal delta.
Modest shifting delta in an awake patient who is on the phone.
Tiny, discrete temporal sharp waves noted only in the initial sections of the record.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These very small polyspike discharges at T2 and T4 suggest a cortical process.  They were only seen in the beginning of the EEG.  The generalized background slowing and bursts of beta and delta may be part of the postictal state or medications used for the status epilepticus.  The markedly slow
background in an awake, conversant patient does, however, suggest a chronic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  62 year old right handed female with diagnosis at age 40 with episode of twitching of the mouth and legs for 5 minutes with intermittent loss of consciousness.  She is here for seizure clarification.

The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness, stage I sleep. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation produce no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen intermittently at F7/T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-60 mV again seen occasionally.  In addition, the patient has multiple bouts of rhythmic mid temporal theta of drowsiness at times in single bursts and wickets frequently seen in both temporal lobes.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Infrequent left anterior temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 30 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, seizure free for the last 3 years.
MEDICATIONS:  Carbatrol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm reaching 50-60 mV.  There is a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta. In relaxed wakefulness, as well as in the transition into early drowsiness, and more remarkably in hyperventilation, there are bursts of frontally predominant 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity.  In relaxed wakefulness, bursts are less than 2.5 seconds in duration, but they are bit more prominent in hyperventilation.  Hyperventilation also produces bursts of rhythmic frontal delta.  During photic stimulation, there are some bursts of more posteriorly predominant delta, some of which are sharply contoured, but without a definitive posterior spike and wave complex.  Head rocking artifact is also noted in photic stimulation.  Deeper stages of sleep are not achieved, but there are brief sections, just very brief epochs, but the patient seems to start to fall asleep with some vertex activity, but sleep is not sustained.
HR:    60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized spike and wave activity for much of which is frontally predominant and relatively symmetric.
Posterior spike and wave activity was also noted.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings have been identified in previous EEGs, but this patient's period of hyperventilation seems to be an activating feature for this individual, but it did not precipitate any clinical features.  The above pattern can be seen in a primary or secondary generalized process.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  70 year old right handed male with Myelodysplastic syndrome, previous history of PRES with seizures.  He has been seizure free for 2 years, July 2010.
MEDICATIONS:  Depakote.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  The patient is drowsy.

As the patient hyperventilates or transitions in and out of drowsiness, the alpha rhythm on the right drops out before the alpha rhythm on the left.  There is some very subtle underlying focal slowing on the right. Photic stimulation does not significantly activate the record.  Drowsiness is characterized by drop out of the alpha rhythm, the subtle right posterior slowing, spindles, and then rare vertex waves.
HR:    66 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Mildly abnormal EEG due to:
A subtle focus of right posterior delta with very subtle disruption of the alpha rhythm on the right.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings have been previously identified.  This follow up EEG does not identify epileptiform features.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 38 year old woman with a history of a left temporal ganglioglioma status post resection in 2009, with seizures in the past 7 months described as having eye twitching.

The patient easily and rapidly goes into stage 2 sleep in less than 10 seconds and activating procedures produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen continuously T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz with an amplitude of 20-70 microvolts in addition a breach rhythm seen in that region.

Focal slowing and breach rhythm in the left midtemporal region.

No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Please note that the patient did appear to easily go to sleep during the recording and clinical consideration for a sleep study is warranted.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  66 year old woman with a history of a motor vehicle accident in 1972 status post coma for 3 months and aneurysm hemorrhage in January 2011 now with seizures, the last one on May 15, 2012, and they state they are now becoming more frequent.

There is an increased amount of beta seen diffusely throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness. During the recording, there is marked amount of rhythmic midtemporal theta of drowsiness which is very sharply contoured but not epileptic.

Breach primarily over the left central occipital region.
Asymmetry of sleep architecture with sleep architecture better formed over the left hemisphere.
No stage II sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 22 minute EEG due to intermittent mild left hemispheric focal slowing.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction that in this case is consistent with the patient's history of aneurysm and a left craniotomy. Breach effect is observed with an underlying skull defect.  No epileptiform discharges are captured.  Stage II sleep is not recorded.  If a clinical suspicion of epilepsy still persists a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 56-year-old male with a stroke in August of 2012, left-sided weakness which resolved, but intermittent left-sided numbness and right ocular issues.  Baseline study for right carotid endarterectomy.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a relatively low voltage background with generous beta.  There is a very subtle asymmetry with somewhat faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.  The alpha rhythm is slightly faster on the left, 12 Hz on the left and 11.5 Hz on the right.  In addition, the faster activity has slightly higher amplitude on the left.  There is occasional, shifting delta from either hemisphere.
Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
Heart rate 84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
A very subtle asymmetry in terms of faster activity and alpha activity on the left.
Occasional shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The focal features are ipsilateral to the patient's recent stroke.  These findings will be used for the patient's operative baseline.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  20 minutes and 26 seconds.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 64-year-old man with a past medical history of a stroke in 2002, epilepsy, headaches, diabetes and dementia.  The patient's seizures are described as loss of consciousness associated with shaking, aggression and confusion.  Last seizure was approximately 1 year ago.
MEDICATIONS:  Current medications:  Vimpat, Keppra, Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  Condition of the recording:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.    Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of low to moderate amplitude 9 Hz alpha that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During drowsiness the posterior dominant rhythm attenuates and diffuse theta appears.  No Stage II sleep is recorded.  Occasional bursts of polymorphic moderate amplitude theta and delta are captured over the left temporal region.  At times the slowing appears to be sharply contoured.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Step photic stimulation results in no change in the background.
FINDINGS:
Mild to moderate focal left temporal slowing.
No epileptiform discharges.
No Stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 21 minute awake and drowsy EEG due to mild to moderate occasional left temporal slowing.  This finding indicates focal dysfunction over the left temporal region, that could be structural in etiology.  No clear epileptiform discharges are captured, however, Stage II sleep is not recorded.  If clinical indication for epilepsy persists a repeat study with sleep may be of benefit.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 50-year-old male with multiple strokes, left hemiparesis, and daily nocturnal seizures with tongue biting and confusion.  Past history of cocaine abuse, now in rehab for 2 months.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Catapres, others seizure medications and medications for depression.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a low voltage EEG in a patient who is quite sleepy, transitioning in and out of stage 2 sleep.  There is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  This low voltage EEG is best reviewed at 3 Hz.  There is rhythmic theta and even some delta noted in the right hemisphere.  Stage 2 sleep is relatively symmetric with vertex waves, K complexes and spindles.  As the patient transitions in and out of sleep, mu activity is noted in wakefulness.  As stage 2 sleep continues, shifting slowing is later noted in stage 2 sleep with a single sharp wave in the left hemisphere in stage 2 sleep.
Photic stimulation does active the record.  Heart rate 60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a challenging, but abnormal EEG due to SHIFTING slowing at times with more rhythmic slowing from the right hemisphere, but occasionally in stage 2 sleep from the left.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Only a single sharp wave was identified from the left which therefore must be considered an artifact.  These findings may be correlated with imaging.  Focal slowing was noted, but unfortunately there was only a single sharp wave.  If additional information is needed for this individual with frequent seizures, inpatient or outpatient video EEG monitoring may be valuable.  The focal slowing on the right fits with a history of the right MCA infarct.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Episode of losing consciousness.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old woman with history of hypertension, hyperlipidemia and borderline diabetes, a right MCA stroke in 2011 as well as drug abuse, presents to the hospital after passing out while driving and does not remember the accident.
MEDICATIONS:  Lovenox, Tylenol, aspirin, hydralazine and other medications.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using a standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.   The patient was recorded during limited wakefulness and sleep. Activating procedures, included photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Heart rate:  60.
The record opens up mainly in sleep and limited wakefulness is captured.  During the limited wakefulness at times posterior dominant rhythm can be seen that reaches 9 Hz but the majority of the time, there is an overall theta during wakefulness.  Otherwise, some normal sleep architecture sleep is stage II and I is seen.
Photic stimulation produces no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges: Excessive theta during limited wakefulness.
Seizures: None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to excessive theta during limited wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific regards to etiology and may be due at least in part to medication effect. No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old man with 2 seizures on 10/11/2012 and 10/17/2012, both events with loss of consciousness, fall, shaking, and confusion.  He feels they are stress related. A past medical history of diabetes, hypertension, and depression.
MEDICATIONS:  Zoloft, Buspar, Klonopin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and a single lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record open to a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and sleep, stage I and stage II.  Activating procedures including hyperventilation and photic stimulation produced no abnormal discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Intermittent F7/T1 focal slowing seen at 2-4Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.  At  times this focal slowing appears to become monomorphic and rhythmic consistent with temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.  At times is also sharply contoured.
HEART RATE:  84 and regular.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to intermittent left anterior temporal slowing as well as intermittent left temporal intermittent rhythmic delta activity, (TIRDA).
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left anterior temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  In addition, the finding of TIRDA has a high correlation with seizures arising from that region.  No actual seizures were seen in this recording.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 23-year-old female with history of childhood seizures, last one in April 2011, describes tonic-clonic activity in her sleep with incontinence, has a history of agenesis of the corpus callosum with right hemiparesis and congenital head deformity.  Most recent seizure was October 15, 2012, multiple seizures in 1 day.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record is mainly in sleep, however, during limited wakefulness, a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is seen over both the right and left hemisphere is slightly higher on the right.  There is also frontocentral beta slightly less prominent over the left hemisphere compared to the right.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness, stage 1 and stage 2 sleep.  Please note that stage 1 vertex waves were noted to be asymmetrical and at times seen more prominently over the left than the right.  However, this only occurs in sleep which suggested these are vertex waves rather than epileptiform discharges.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Paucity of faster frequencies over the left hemisphere compared to the right and some slowing in the left frontal region.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left frontal F3 slowing as well as paucity of faster frequencies.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontal region, which may have a correlation with a lesion in that region.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were clearly seen.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Routine EEG.
DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 55-year-old female with prior EEG and presents with history of diabetes, hypertension, anemia, hyperlipidemia, coronary artery disease, bypass surgery.
MEDICATIONS:  Patient is taking medications for diabetes and high blood pressure.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using the standard International 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed and photic stimulation was performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness and stage I and II sleep.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, alpha rhythm is 8-8.5 Hz in frequency, 30-50 microvolts in amplitude seen in occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness which is distributed symmetrically.  There was a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  A stage I and stage II sleep is characterized with disappearance of alpha rhythm, slowing of the background activity, and absence of motion and eye-blink artifact as well as presence of the vertex sharp waves, sleep spindles, and K complexes.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple frequencies and did not resolve in a driving response.  Heart rate was 60-70 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is mildly abnormal EEG due to excess theta activity during wakefulness.  There was no epileptiform discharge or seizure activity noted during this recording.  The above finding could be due to metabolic, toxic, hypoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to effect of sedating medication, bilateral cerebral dysfunction, degenerative brain disease.  No epileptiform abnormalities or seizures were captured or recorded.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 50-year-old man with a history of multiple strokes with resultant left hemiparesis and spasticity with reported daily generalized tonoclonic convulsions.

CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated low amplitude 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient, with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  During sleep vertex waves,  sleep spindles and K complexes are captured.  Frequent polymorphic theta and delta activity at lower amplitudes are captured over the right mid temporal region.  Hyperventilation is not performed. Photic stimulation results in no change in the background.
FINDINGS:
Intermittent moderate right mid temporal slowing.
Stage II sleep.
No epileptiform charges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal awake and asleep 23 minute EEG due to intermittent moderate right mid temporal slowing.  This finding indicates underlying cerebral dysfunction, likely structural, in  this patient is consistent with a prior history of a right MCA territory stroke.  No epileptiform discharges were captured.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is an 18-year-old man with a history of seizures since 16 years of age.  Last seizure was approximately in 01/2012.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of  well-formed and modulated 10 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  Frequent lambda is observed.  Sleep is not captured.  There are frequent 1 to 2 second bursts of generalized frontally predominant spike and wave discharges and polyspike and wave discharges.  These discharges occur at approximately 3 to 3.5 Hz.  These generalized discharges become more frequent with hyperventilation and persistent throughout the recording.  The patient is able to tap and count correctly throughout these bursts.  Hyperventilation increases frequency of generalized spike and wave bursts.  Stepped photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving.
FINDINGS:  Frequent 1 to 2 second bursts of generalized frontally predominant spike and wave discharges and polyspike and wave discharges occurring at 3 to 3.5 Hz.  No electrographic seizures.  No stage II sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 24 minute awake only EEG due to frequent brief bursts of generalized frontally predominant spike and wave and polyspike and wave discharges.  In a proper clinical setting this EEG is consistent with a diagnosis of idiopathic generalized epilepsy.  No electrographic seizures are captured.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman admitted on October 23, with fatigue and a fever found to have a right frontal subdural hematoma and a left MCA infarct.
MEDICATIONS:  None reported.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is an awake and drowsy EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  Sections of the record include a rhythmic approximately 7 Hz theta frequency background with a 7-8 Hz alpha rhythm, but much of the record include significantly more slower rhythmic mixed theta and delta.  Superimposed upon this is some focal slowing with a bit more arrhythmic alpha on the left compared to the right and disruption of faster frequency activity.  In addition, occasional sharp waves are noted independently at T4, P4 and T1.  Sharp waves are relatively infrequent.  Stimulation of the patient produces an alerting response with an increase in the faster frequency activity.  Rare triphasic waves were observed.  Heart rate 97 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing.
Intermittent, paroxysmal slowing.
Superimposed asymmetry with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left in comparison to the right.
Independent sharp waves seen from either hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a diffuse disturbance of cerebral function affecting gray and white matter.  In addition, a structural or functional process on the left should be considered.  There are infrequent sharp waves seen from either hemisphere.  These findings may even be correlated with imaging and clinical history.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Followup from seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded while in wakefulness.
Activating procedures were not performed.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, phenobarbital, Serax, thiamine, aspirin, Unasyn.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 61-year-old man found to have hyponatremia and recurrent focal right arm shaking, focal seizures.

There is some frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture seen.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Overall, the EEG has a pretty normal background, but at times, there is a burst of monomorphic frontal delta, consistent with frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity that lasts, at most, 3 to 4 seconds.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:
Focal slow wave over T3, seen frequently in a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
Intermittent bursts of FIRDA seen throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left temporal slowing, as well as intermittent FIRDA.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 47-year-old woman with a history of a seizure in May of 2012, cerebral cavernoma and childhood ventriculostomy.  The patient required Gamma Knife therapy for vascular pathology in June of 2012.  Unsteady gait, evaluate for possible medication discontinuation.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Pravachol, lisinopril.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed, but not hyperventilation.

Craniotomy defect was noted with some irregularity on the right.  Prominent lateral rectus eye movement artifact was also noted.  In relaxed wakefulness there was a small amount of frontal theta noted intermittently.
Photic stimulation elicited scant driving.
Heart rate 90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very mildly abnormal EEG due to:  Intermittent bifrontal theta.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings described above are subtle and are nonspecific in nature.  They may be seen in the context of a bihemispheric process as described above or they may be seen with the use of some medications, although not typically with the medications this patient is receiving.  There were no epileptiform features identified.

TYPE OF STUDY:  Outpatient EEG.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 37-year-old woman with epilepsy since birth.  Birth and developmental history unknown, but strong family history of epilepsy on her father's side.  Patient also has severe migraines.  She describes her last seizure as screaming, crying, and epistaxis.  Typically, seizures not so severe.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, phenobarbital, Zoloft, Prilosec, Risperdal, Spiriva, albuterol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized with 9.5 Hz, 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm.  The alpha rhythm reaches 10 Hz, 70 microvolts with occasional posterior slow waves of youth.  Features of drowsiness include attenuation of the alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation does not significantly activate the record.  Photic stimulation elicits a driving response.  Heart rate 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were identified in this record.  In this individual with lifelong, refractory epilepsy, a follow-up study capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 68-year-old woman admitted to the hospital several days ago with aphasia and a 1 week history of language difficulties, resolving and right-sided weakness.
MEDICATIONS:  Aspirin, lisinopril, others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is diffusely slow and poorly organized.  Both hemispheres are somewhat slow and disorganized with a posterior dominant rhythm of 6-7 Hz.  There is disruption of faster frequency activity noted from the left hemisphere.  There are bursts of frontally prominent regular or irregular delta noted.  Rhythmic delta activity is also observed in the occipital regions, right or left with an occipital sharp wave which is almost at the midline.  In addition, there are rare left central sharp waves maximum at C3 in wakefulness, there is an increase in more rhythmic theta frequency activity and the alpha rhonchi is a bit better defined on the right.  Photic stimulation did not significantly activate the record.  Heart rate sometimes irregular, 72 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing and disorganization.
Superimposed focal features with disruption of faster frequency activity on the left compared to the right.
Sharp waves noted including left central as well as others that are occipital in nature.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG supports a bihemispheric process involving gray and white matter.  In addition, focal features, congruent with the stroke history include disruption of faster frequency activity and the sharp waves described above.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old woman found confused on the floor with bladder and bowel incontinence, with hypertension, diabetes, chronic renal disease on hemodialysis, history of DVT and PE.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, morphine, lorazepam.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with the addition of anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during lethargy.  Activating procedures were not performed.  Spike wave detection, seizure detection software, patient events and nurses notes were all used to review the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with no posterior dominant rhythm or frontocentral beta.  There is no normal sleep architecture.  No activating procedures were performed.  Overall, the background consists of mainly delta frequency at 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-40 microvolts seen diffusely with intermittent bursts of theta.  Sometimes the patient arouses and there is some diffuse muscle artifact seen.  In addition, there is frequent triphasic waves which appear to be bifrontal predominant symmetric at times seen more rhythmically at 1 Hz.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Generalized slow waves described above and triphasics.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to moderate to severe generalized slowing in addition to triphasic waves.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction which may be due at least in part to metabolic effect or a metabolic disturbance.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 66-year-old woman with epilepsy.  The patient has a complex neurological history, was in a coma in 1972 for 3 months after a motor vehicle accident, past history of an aneurysmal hemorrhage and then an assault in January 2011.  Currently she has spells up to 6 to 8 times per day.  In addition, she also has a feeling of being unwell after walking several blocks.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, aspirin, lisinopril, propranolol.
INTRODUCTION:  Continuous video EEG monitoring was performed in the unit using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This patient was extremely drowsy.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Random wakefulness and sleep:  Much of the record includes stage II sleep with vertex waves, K-complex, spindles and POSTS.  The patient arouses briefly.  There are some bursts of posterior predominant mixed theta delta which can be seen in wakefulness or sleep.  There is no specific mention of a craniotomy, but there is a suggestion of a possible breach on the left with a little bit of wicket like activity.
As the patient transitions in and out of stage II sleep, there is occasional, sharply contoured slowing in the left temporal region.
By 8:00 a.m. on the morning of 11/21/2012 the patient is more consistently awake, but by the afternoon she is drifting off to sleep again.  Occasional wicket activity was identified.
Heart rate:  84 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal long term video EEG monitoring session for a patient of this age due to:
Occasional bursts of more posteriorly predominant slowing seen in the transition into sleep.
Sharply contoured left temporal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Wicket activity was identified.  There is sharply contoured slowing, but no definitive spike and wave or sharp waves with after going slow waves identified in this record.  These findings may be correlated with imaging.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  He is a 63-year-old man with history of epilepsy since age 29, has mainly tonic/clonic seizures refractory to Dilantin in relation to medication noncompliance.  Currently he is having 1-2 seizures per month.  He has a history of alcohol abuse and cocaine abuse in the past.

Activating procedures included photic stimulation produces no abnormal  discharges.   The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 72-year-old woman, found confused with incontinence.  Status post prolonged intubation, but now awake and alert.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, midazolam, Coumadin, Decadron.

There is a bit of shifting arrhythmic delta activity, right greater than left.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in slowing, an increase in the arrhythmic delta activity and an increase in the focality with a bit more left-sided slowing.

Background slowing with excess theta and a slightly slow alpha.
Shifting slowing, left greater than right in drowsiness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old woman with cerebral aneurysm which was previously coiled. The patient was admitted November 8 for inability to move the right side and then December 3 for hypotension. Now with intermittent episodes of unresponsiveness.

There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  No sleep was captured.
