LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Nearly 23 minutes.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation was performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 46-year-old woman with past medical history of seizures, right hemispheric stroke, hepatitis C, who presents with a possible seizure.  As per history, patient had an episode characterized by left upper extremity shaking that lasted a few minutes.  This is the second such episode since August of 2012.  Patient stopped taking Keppra about 2 days ago.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, metformin, Coumadin, insulin, Zocor.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is right to left interhemispheric asymmetry with slow waveforms over the right hemisphere.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of a well formed and modulated 9 to 10 Hertz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  Over the left hemisphere, there is preserved anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the right hemisphere is unstable and reaches about 9 Hertz alpha.  There is no clear anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background over the right hemisphere consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta activity with under-riding faster frequencies.  Slowing is more pronounced over the anterior temporal/frontal region.  The patient briefly falls asleep by the end of the recording.  Sleep spindles are captured only over the left hemisphere.  Brief 1 to 3-second bursts of frontally predominant rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) are captured.  Occasional poorly formed, sharply contoured waveforms observed over the right midtemporal region with phase reversal over T4-T6 electrode.  Hyperventilation is not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation results in occipital driving only over the left hemisphere.
FINDINGS:
Continuous moderate slowing over the right hemisphere, most pronounced over the anterior temporal/frontal region.
Sharp waves over the right mid temporal region.
No electrographic seizures.
Asymmetry of sleep architecture with sleep better formed over the left hemisphere.
Asymmetrical occipital driving with driving only observed over the left hemisphere.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 23-minute awake and briefly asleep EEG, due to continuous focal slowing over the right hemisphere that is most pronounced over the frontotemporal region and occasional epileptiform discharges over the right mid midtemporal region. These findings indicate focal cerebral dysfunction that carries increased epileptogenic potential. FIRDA is observed in encephalopathies, increase intracranial pressure, deep white matter lesions. No electrographic seizures are captured.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 59-year-old male with a history of alcohol abuse and epilepsy, off seizure medications for a decade admitted this morning with status epilepticus.  Date of study is December 14.  CAT scan shows chronic ischemic cerebrovascular disease.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Ativan, Versed, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the emergency room using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was somnolent, but sometimes responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly slow.  Superimposed upon the slow background there are sharp waves, some periodic slowing and some periodic sharps noted in the left  hemisphere typically at T1, but with some variability, T1, F7 and T3.  Stimulation of the patient does produce an alerting response with a glimpse of an alpha on the right, but the patient remains somnolent.  Unfortunately, stimulation of the patient also produces a fair amount of artifact.  In an averaged reference, the epileptiform activity is maximum at F7 with a variable field in the left anterior temporal or frontotemporal.
Heart rate 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Focal slowing from the left frontotemporal region.
Sharp waves, periodic complexes and periodic delta in the left frontal and frontotemporal region with variability.
Background slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  As the recording continues, with stimulation of the patient there is an increase in faster frequency activity on the right.  However, the periodic activity and the sharp waves on the left have not abated, although there are no clinical seizures.  Ongoing clinical evaluation is warranted.

DIAGNOSIS:  Altered mental status.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 48-year-old female who was admitted for change in mental status.  On arrival, she was found to be aphasic.  She was confused, but responsive to her name.  Past medical history is significant for dilated cardiomyopathy, status post AICD and LVAD, LV thrombosis on Coumadin, atrial fibrillation, left MCA stroke, and peripheral neuropathy.
MEDICATIONS:  The patient's medications include Plavix, warfarin, ceftazidime, simvastatin, Ambien, Coreg, lorazepam, midazolam, and Topamax.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed at bedside using the standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1-channel of EKG monitoring.  This tracing captures patient in an obtunded stuporous state. Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the stuporous state, the background activity was characterized by diffuse slowing consisting of sharply contoured delta wave slower on the left side with a frequency of 3-3.5 Hz high amplitude with sharp wave activities most prominent in the left central parietal and occipital regions There were also Triphasic waves seen intermittently with an Anterior- posterior gradient/ occurring with a frequency of 1-1.2 Hz.  Heart rate was 90 to 100 beats per minute.  Photic stimulation and hyperventilation were not performed.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to diffuse slowing with sharply contoured delta waves, and Triphasic waves and sharp wave discharges most pronounced in left posterior quadrant without evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Slowing of background activity and Triphasic waves are indicative of metabolic, toxic, hypoxic or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively it could be due to the effects of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction.  The presence of sharp wave discharges are indicative of hyperexcitability of cerebral cortex that places this patient at risk for partial seizures.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman with epilepsy since age 13.  Past history of grand mal seizures, but seizure free until June of 2012.  The patient now has episodes of poor responsiveness while awake with eyes open.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol and Neurontin.
INTRODUCTION:  This is a digital video EEG performed in the lab using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is an 8-Hertz alpha rhythm.  Excess 7-Hertz theta activity is observed in the background.  Very brief, stage 2 sleep includes vertex waves and spindles.  Hyperventilation did not activate the record, but photic stimulation elicited a driving response.  Heart rate was 84 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Excess theta.
Wicked activity was identified in drowsiness.  This is a normal phenomenon.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 48-year-old woman with a past medical history of heart failure status post LVAD and AICD, left ventricular thrombus, atrial fibrillation, left MCA stroke, declining mental status, and DNR-1 as of today.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Topamax, __________, Lexapro, Coreg, and ceftriaxone.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient is intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This EEG is markedly disorganized.  It is also sharply contoured.  The overall background includes rhythmic beta and triphasic waves.  Shifting slowing was identified.  In this sharply contoured background, focal sharp waves are identified in T4, C3, T1, and right posterior temporal.  Intermittent attenuations were noted in the background.  Stimulation of the patient did not activate the record.
Heart rate 102 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to the following abnormalities:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Intermittent attenuation.
Triphasic waves.
Occasional isolated sharp waves seen from either hemisphere.
This EEG is similar to the prior EEG.  Toxic metabolic disturbances may accentuate the underlying pattern described above.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  Approximately 21 minutes.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with position of additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  Patient is a 65-year-old man with history of cardiac rest status post prolonged CPR now with diffuse myoclonus concerning for status epilepticus.
MEDICATIONS:  Valproic acid, lorazepam and 4 mg vecuronium given during the EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient, Until approximately 10 minutes into the recording the EEG consists of high amplitude diffuse irregular EMG artifact with frequent brief periods of discontinuity.
At approximately 8 minutes into the recording, 4 mg of vecuronium is administered.  Approximately 10 minutes into the recording, EMG artifact disappears.  Once EMG artifact is cleared, the background consists of low to moderate amplitude, generalized frontally predominant, spikes and poly spikes with after-going slow waves that occur at approximately 1.5 to 4 Hz.  These discharges appear both rhythmically and semi-rhythmically.  They do not organize into clear electrographic seizures.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
FINDINGS: 1.  Frontally predominant generalized 1.5 to 4 Hz G-PEDs and quasi PEDs.
2. No clear electrographic Seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 21-minute electroencephalogram due to continuous generalized frontally predominant epileptiform discharges that occur rhythmically and semi-rhythmically at approximately 1.5 to 4 Hz.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.  This electroencephalogram pattern indicates high cortical irritability, high risk for status epilepticus and in post anoxic brain injury indicates a poor chance for full neurological recovery.  These findings were conveyed to the neurology consultation team.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 28-year-old woman with epilepsy, seizure free for perhaps 9 years.  Patient had an unusual event on the 27th with involuntary jerking of the upper extremities without loss of consciousness followed by neck ache and headache.  Found to have a right vertebral artery dissection.
MEDICATIONS:  Lamictal, heparin, Protonix.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is well organized.  There is a 10.7-Hz alpha rhythm.  There is focal slowing noted in the right mid-to-posterior temporal region.  Hyperventilation was performed with good effort, producing rhythmic, high-amplitude slowing.  There were rare bursts of paroxysmal slowing, but no definitive 3-Hz spike and wave slowing noted with hyperventilation.  Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in rhythmicity of the background.  The focal slowing in the right posterior quadrant was less prominent as the patient became drowsy.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response with some lambda as well.  There was a suggestion of a photoparoxysmal response with the 11-Hz stimulation and very subtle spike and wave activity elicited bilaterally with 15-Hz stimulation.  These were discrete bursts of 5-Hz spike and wave activity at 15 and then some paroxysmal changes again at 17 Hz stimuli with spike and wave activity.
Heart rate 84 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal electroencephalogram due to:
Discrete 3- to 5-Hz spike and wave activity noted with photic stimulation at faster flash frequencies.
Focal slowing noted from the right mid-to-posterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The spike and wave activity has been noted in this patient's many previous EEGs.  Compared to previous studies, this EEG seems to have a little less in the way of spike and wave activity.  The focal slowing is congruent with the recent strip.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Transient left-sided weakness and seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 49-year-old man with history of fungal sinusitis, status post drainage surgery with history of hypertension, diabetes, hyperlipidemia, and left-sided weakness and 2 generalized tonic-clonic seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, insulin, Protonix, aspirin, and Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during limited wakefulness and mainly in sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record reveals limited wakefulness during which a posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz can be seen at best and appears to be reactive to eye opening.  There is diffuse beta seen throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded mainly in sleep stage 1 and stage 2.  Activating procedures were not performed.
Heart rate 84.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow waves seen at F8/T3 and at times with a large field that can be seen over F3 and sometimes even FP2 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and an amplitude of 20-50 microvolts.  One of these focal slowings had a very sharply contoured transient, but not clearly epileptiform.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left frontotemporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left frontotemporal region, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 31-year-old right handed woman with childhood epilepsy.  History of absence seizures.  Tonic/clonic seizures.  The patient experienced as exacerbation of her epilepsy with a prolonged fugue state in November following a bout of gastroenteritis.
MEDICATIONS:  Carbatrol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  Technically, a significant head rocking artifact was noted, particularly in the right occipital region.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a high amplitude 9 Hz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.  Minimal drowsiness is characterized by a decrease of eye movement and anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.
Hyperventilation generates a vigorous hyperventilation response with bursts of rhythmic high amplitude rhythmic mixed beta delta.  In addition, there is frontally predominant underlying 3-5 Hz spike and wave activity noted in brief bursts and a little bit of irregularity in the posterior regions.  A handful of the bursts of paroxysmal slowing are posteriorly predominant.
Photic stimulation also elicited rare spike and wave activity which was frontally predominant and a single burst was noted as the patient became drowsy following photic stimulation towards the end of the record.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to:
Three to 5 Hz spike and wave activity.
Occasional occipitally predominant slowing noted in hyperventilation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  These findings are similar to previous EEGs and support a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.  As has been seen in previous studies, this EEG may be compatible with a primary secondarily generalized mechanism for seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 55-year-old woman with lifelong epilepsy, previous nuchal cord, severe psychiatric symptoms now with episodes of almost a visual hallucination and a recent worsening seizure when she was taken off of extended release medications.
MEDICATIONS:  Tegretol XR.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This is an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness the background EEG is disorganized.  There is a glimpse of a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with excess theta.  There are bursts of sharps and contoured shifting noted.  These are maximum in the temporal regions.  Hyperventilation seems to accentuate left temporal focal slowing.  As the patient drifts off to sleep, there is a bit more right temporal focal slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
Heart rate 96 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
A disorganized background.
Sharply contoured slowing noted from either hemisphere.
Sharply contoured slowing with phase reversal noted in both the left and the right anterior temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Although previous EEGs were not available, this is a patient with a long history of an abnormal EEG.  This EEG supports a bihemispheric process.  No seizures were recorded.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  23 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 56-year-old woman who now presents with change in mental status.  The patient has a past medical history of coronary artery disease, hypertension, diabetes, COPD, and non-epileptic events.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and others.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with an additional T1 and T2 electrode and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm and no clear anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of a low amplitude polymorphic theta and delta activity.  No normal sleep architecture is captured.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.  A regular heart rate is noted in the single EKG lead.
FINDINGS:
Mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.
No sleep.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal 23-minute study due to mild to moderate diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  This finding indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction. The lack of epileptiform discharges in a routine EEG does not preclude the clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.

REASON FOR EEG:  Mysterious seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 44-year-old man with history of seizures and a strange spell a week ago.
MEDICATIONS:  None mentioned.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and drowsiness.
Activating procedures, including hyperventilation and photic stimulation, produce no abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:  Focal slow waves seen occasionally at T3 with a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV.
Seizures:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to left mid temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old male with alcohol withdrawal or hyponatremia related seizures characterized by right facial twitching.  The patient had 2 to 3 episodes in the emergency room recently in November of 2012, after missing medications.  He had another seizure on February 5.  No other information is available.  He lives in Andorra Woods.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Vimpat, Seroquel, Ativan, many others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab  using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was completed, but hyperventilation was not possible.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The awake EEG is quite abnormal.  The right hemisphere is nearly normal with a 9 Hz alpha rhythm and a pattern with generous beta.  The left hemisphere has a continuous, periodic complete with a generous field of spread throughout the left hemisphere, but maximum in the left mid to posterior temporal region.  This also has significant involvement in the left parietal and occipital region.  Using an average reference, this activity is nearly maximum at O1 with a phase reversal at P3.  The phase reverses at P3-C3.  Features of drowsiness including increase in beta is noted throughout the right hemisphere, less so on the left.  Photic stimulation does not activate the record.  Heart rate is 72 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
A complex, epileptiform discharge in the left hemisphere with some variability and even a polyphasic component.  This discharge may begin in the left frontocentral region, but its highest amplitude is in the left occipital region with a generous field of spread in the left posterior quadrant.
This is essentially a periodic complex without frequency evolution.
Disruption faster frequency activity from the left hemisphere.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The periodic complexes in the left hemisphere are similar to previous EEG, including previous EEG monitoring.  These findings should be placed in the appropriate clinical context.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 35-year-old woman with non-small cell lung cancer, metastasis to brain with whole brain radiation in 2011, now with right frontal EVD.  The patient needed to be evaluated for seizures after she became obtunded after bronchoscopy requiring intubation.  The patient transferred to Temple for evaluation of either hypoxic cerebral injury or cerebral edema.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, Serax, Decadron, propofol drip, others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  The patient was intubated and comatose.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG is markedly abnormal.  The primary frequency in the background is a mixture of delta and theta.  There is a slight asymmetry between the 2 hemispheres.  There tends to be a bit higher amplitude rhythmic delta in the right frontal regions compared to the left.
Stimulation of the patient does not activate the record.
Heart rate:  90 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to:
Replacement of normal background with marked generalized slowing.
Shifting slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The use of sedative or hypnotic medications can play a roll in the pattern described above, but the marked background slowing with paucity of faster frequency is more supportive of a severe, diffuse bihemispheric disturbance.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 63 year old woman with a recent episode of blurry vision and expressive aphasia for 1 hour, evaluate for TIA versus complex partial seizure.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the laboratory using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel EKG.  Photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with a generous amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta.
Despite the eye movement artifacts, as the patient transitions into drowsiness, there is occasional, focal slowing with beta noted in the left hemisphere, particularly frontotemporal frontocentral.
Photic stimulation elicited brief bilateral driving.
Heart rate 60 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a mildly abnormal EEG due to focal slowing noted in drowsiness in the left frontocentral frontotemporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The findings described above are of unclear clinical significance.  They may be seen in the context of TIA or cerebrovascular ischemia.  No definitive epileptiform features were identified.  Because similar features can be seen in the context of a focal seizure, if needed, a repeat tracing capturing deeper stages of sleep is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 49-year-old male with history of frontal sinusitis, hypertension, left sided weakness, and new onset seizures 01/07/2013, now with neck pain, dizziness, and balance problems.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In apparent wakefulness, the overall background EEG is somewhat slow with rhythmic theta and delta.  It is difficult to define this alpha rhythm in an otherwise low voltage EEG.  Generous frontal central beta activity was noted.
Hyperventilation produced prominent rhythmic bilateral 3-4 Hz activity.
Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.  In addition, the bursts of slowing were a bit more prominent on the left, some of which were sharply contoured, but without definitive sharp waves.
Heart rate:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Generalized background slowing noted intermittently in wakefulness.
Scant alpha rhythm (this is not considered necessarily pathological).
Background disorganization.
Superimposed focal slowing more so from the left frontal temporal region.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  In comparison to a previous EEG, 01/07/2013, the focal slowing does not appear to be so prominent, but there may be more generalized background slowing.  The previous EEG was primarily in sleep. Consideration for both a focal and a diffuse disturbance of cerebral dysfunction is appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 61-year-old woman with epilepsy, seizure free for the past 3 years.  Previous craniotomy with residual left sided deficit and cranial defect C4 to P4, as well as T6.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation was deferred.  Photic stimulation was completed.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is a fair amount of muscle artifact noted in the background and there is a slight degree of disorganization in both hemispheres.  The most prominent features in this record include intermittent focal slowing in the right hemisphere with spread to the midline with bursts of higher amplitude, right frontocentral delta.  In the context of a breech rhythm, there is some sharply contoured discharges at F4, but without after going slow wave.
Photic stimulation elicited a driving response somewhat more apparent on the left than the right, but present bilaterally.
Features of sleep included the appearance of frontal delta, right more so than the left.  Brief stage I sleep with vertex waves was noted, but stage II sleep was not sustained.  Heart rate 66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Intermittent, focal slowing noted in the right hemisphere most prominent in drowsiness or sleep with a generous field of spread into the right hemisphere and to the midline.
Disruption of faster frequency activity in the right frontocentral region.
Mild slowing and disorganization on the left.
Clinical correlation, no definitive epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 49-year-old male with first ever seizure 3 weeks ago, characterized by left leg twitching, left leg weakness and numbness.  Found to have right frontal parenchymal contusion and right subdural hematoma in November 2002.  Admitted on the 21st for numbness.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra and Lovenox.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  This is an awake and drowsy record.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm.  There is prominent, frontal central beta.  In wakefulness an a bit more prominently in drowsiness, there is focal slowing from the right frontal central and central temporal regions.  This is primarily characterized by slower delta, but with some disruption in faster frequency activity.  Hyperventilation was performed early in the record, and accentuates the right frontal central focal slowing.  Features of drowsiness included increase in beta.  The intermittent right frontal central focal slowing persists.
Photic stimulation elicited harmonic and super harmonic driving.
Heart rate 78 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to focal slowing from the right frontal central region with occasional disruption of frequency activity in that area.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is most supportive of a structural or functional process in the right frontal central region.  No epileptiform features were identified.  As this patient recovers from the head injury, a follow-up study may be of value.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 24-year-old woman with history of sexual abuse and mental disease with a motor vehicle accident in June, since then has been having seizures that month and just had a premature baby on 02/01/2013.
ARTIFACTS:  None.
MEDICATIONS:  Cannot remember medications.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  Patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures include hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9-10 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is normal frontal central beta.  The patient was recorded in wakeful and stage I and stage II of sleep.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation which produced no abnormal discharge, however, during photic stimulation there was event which I will describe in the next section.  Stage I and stage II sleep were seen.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Focal slow wave seen intermittently at T3 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz and amplitude of 20-60 microvolts.
EPISODES:  During photic stimulation, specifically at 11 Hz, the patient all of the sudden starting shaking her head side to side followed by generalized shaking in an irregular fashion of her whole body while she had her eyes closed.  This continued to occur for about 3 minutes, at which point the patient stopped and appeared to be tired.  During the recording there was a lot of diffuse artifact, however, in between the shaking normal posterior dominant rhythm can be seen and no epileptiform correlate was seen during the episode.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal electroencephalogram due to left mid temporal focal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of focal cerebral dysfunction in the left mid temporal region, which is nonspecific in regards to etiology.  The episode described above had no EEG correlate and is consistent with the diagnosis of psychogenic nonepileptic event.  No seizures or actual epileptiform discharges were seen.

MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
HISTORY:  A 52-year-old with Down syndrome and new onset tonic/clonic seizure in December 2012.  Seizure with loss of consciousness and incontinence.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is 7 Hz alpha rhythm in a pattern with generous beta.  In apparent wakefulness, intermittent rhythmic theta was noted.  In addition to this theta, there are intermittent burst of somewhat irregular slowing noted bilaterally.
The patient transitioned in and out of sleep with vertex waves in snore arousals.
Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was drifting off to sleep and did produce a driving response at faster flash frequencies.
Hyperventilation did not activate the record.
Heart rate 66 bpm.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG for an adult of this age due to:
Slowing of the alpha rhythm.
Some unusual bursts of shifting slowing in sleep particularly in the central regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATIONS:  This patient seems to awaken frequently from sleep or has a fair amount of muscle artifact in sleep.  A more prolonged sleep record maybe helpful to search for epileptiform activity in this middle-aged adult with Down syndrome.  There are no previous EEGs available for comparison in term of the slow alpha rhythm for an adult of this age.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 53-year-old left-handed gentleman with liver metastases, at induction to anesthesia was noted to have an episode of staring, unresponsiveness, followed by one minute generalized shaking without incontinence or tongue biting.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the bedside in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was relatively somnolent.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness, the background is diffusely slow and the patient is relatively somnolent with at best a theta frequency background. There are some bursts of shifting slowing noted in the background. Brief eye opening was noted and the patient was able to provide the year and the season as winter with more of a theta background and some shifting slowing a bit more on the right compared to the left.  Occasional FIRDA was noted.  Features of stage II sleep included vertex waves and spindles.
Photic stimulation was performed at the bedside.
Scant photic driving was noted.
Heart rate 128 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to
Background slowing.
Shifting slowing.
Frontal intermittent rhythmic delta activity.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No epileptiform features were noted.  Overall, this EEG is most compatible with a toxic or metabolic encephalopathy.  If epilepsy and seizures are an important consideration, a follow up tracing may be of value.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 53-year-old gentleman, admitted on 12th, had an episode of unresponsiveness prior to induction of anesthesia for right hepatectomy.  He had a tonic-clonic seizure on 15th.  Arachnoid cyst.
MEDICATIONS:  Fentanyl, piperacillin and tazobactam.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  The patient was intubated and poorly responsive.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a postictal EEG recorded at 11 a.m.  The initial EEG is low voltage diffusely slow at central beta.  The primary frequencies are low-voltage delta with smaller amounts of beta and theta.
As the recording continues, stimulation of the patient produces an alerting response with faster frequency activity.
Over the course of the record, there was an increase in theta in the background.  In addition, the patient seems to be moving a bit or has some very slow eye movements at the end.
Heart rate 140 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a markedly abnormal EEG due to marked background slowing, improving somewhat overtime.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The marked background slowing may be part of this patient's metabolic disorder or due to the use of sedative-hypnotic medications.  No focal or epileptiform features were seen, and there were no specific hallmarks of metabolic encephalopathy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is an 82-year-old male with change in mental status, found to have bilateral subdural hematoma, most pronounced on the right side.  He fell on 02/13/2013, status post evacuation on left hemisphere.  The patient is currently somnolent and with toxic metabolic encephalopathy secondary to sepsis.  The patient has a trochlear implant and he has a skull defect on the right side.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the ICU using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In a lethargic state, the background activity is characterized by a generalized slowing in the delta and theta-frequency range. There is hemispheric asymmetry characterized by attenuation and slowing in right cerebral hemisphere. There is a excess theta activity well formed in left cerebral hemisphere.  There are intermittent delta activity, beta seen with a frequency of 1 to 1.2 Hz lasting for 2-3 seconds.  There are intermittent sharp waves arising from the left parietal-occipital regions most pronounced in P3 with field spread to C3 and O1, occasionally intermixed with the burst of left parieto-temporal slowing.  Heart rate was 70 to 80 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background activity.
Presence of theta burst.
Attenuation of the background activity in the right cerebral hemisphere.
Left parieto-occipital sharp wave discharges with no evolution, intermixed with temporoparietal slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Diffuse slowing of the background activity could be due to toxic, metabolic, hypoxic, infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to sedating medications or cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  The theta burst could also be due to increased intracranial pressure, metabolic encephalopathy, or deep midline lesions in the brain.  Right hemispheric attenuation of the background could be due to right subdural hematoma.  The presence of intermittent sharp wave discharges in the left parieto-occipital region is suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity of that region and place this patient at higher risk for partial seizures.

Recording length is 21 minutes.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the record opens, there is a symmetric 10 Hz posterior dominant rhythm that is of medium amplitude and is reactive to eye opening.  There was a small amount of frontocentral beta activity that is symmetrically distributed over the frontocentral regions bilaterally.  Throughout the recording, there is intermittent focal slowing noted over the left hemisphere.  This is maximal in the frontotemporal and frontocentral regions.  This is characterized by brief epochs of 5 to 6 Hz theta activity and rare very brief epochs of 2 to 3 Hz low amplitude delta activity.  When this is seen, it does disrupt the integrity of the posterior dominant rhythm on the left.  In addition to the focal slowing, there are sharp transient waves identified over the left frontal region.  These are not frankly epileptiform but are suggestive potentially of actual sharp waves.  There are no electrographic seizures detected and there were no clinical events denoted by the patient.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and did not induce a significant photic driving response.  The heart rate was between 60 and 90 beats during the recording.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG capturing wakefulness through drowsiness due to the presence of focal slowing over the left frontotemporal and frontocentral regions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The presence of focal slowing may suggest a structural brain lesion in the left hemisphere.  Sharp transient waves are not frankly epileptiform but may be suggestive of an epileptiform discharge over the left hemisphere.  Clinical correlation is suggested.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  As the tracing begins, the patient is in stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  With stimulation as the patient awakens from sleep, brief, frontal polyspike complexes were observed.  This was followed by a 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm and then new activity of 10 Hz although testing was not performed to confirm the presence of new.
Hyperventilation was performed after this which did not produce an alerting response.  Following hyperventilation, the patient drifted back into stage 2 sleep with vertex wave, K-complexes, spindles and posts.
Photic stimulation was remarkable for photoelectric artifact.
Heart rate:  60 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is a subtly abnormal EEG due to rare, frontally predominant polyspike activity which was elicited when the patient was awakened from stage 2 sleep.  This activity is approximately 6.5 Hz.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Although the epileptiform activity described above is subtle and is seen in a record with frontal muscle artifact, there is a clear frontal 6.5 Hz spike and wave or polyspike and wave discharge noted in the arousal from sleep.  This seems to be frontally predominant and bilaterally symmetric and more compatible with a generalized mechanism for epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 64-year-old man who presented with right-sided seizures; Past medical history include: Hypertension, cirrhosis and CVA.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Keppra, and the patient received 8 mg of Ativan a few hours before the recording.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 system of electrode placement and one channel EKG.  The long-term record was reviewed for abnormalities and clinical events.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  Interictal EEG:  The recording from 04/15/2013 to 04/16/2013 was characterized by diffuse slowing.  There was also continuous polymorphic slowing at T3 in the 4-5 Hz range intermixed with 2-3 Hz frequency, which was frequently sharply contoured.  Occasional sharp waves were noted at T3.
From 10 p.m. onwards, the amount of sharp waves had significantly decreased. Towards the end of the recording, no sharp waves were seen.
Ictal Events:  There was one push button at 8:51 p.m., during which time clinically the patient was moving around.
Ictal EEG:  There was no EEG correlate to the push button event at 8:51 p.m.
Some sleep element characterized by sleep spindles were noted, but there was no definite sleep architecture recorded.
IMPRESSION:  This long-term EEG recording is abnormal due to:
Diffuse bilateral slowing.
Focal left T3 continuous polymorphic slowing in the theta and delta range sharply contoured.
Sharp waves at T3 without evolution.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:
The generalized slowing is suggestive of a diffuse process, such as toxic metabolic process versus medication induced versus a postictal state.
Left focal slowing, which is continuous and most pronounced in the left frontocentral and mid temporal regions is suggestive of an underlying structural abnormality, which is consistent with a known stroke in that region.
The left temporal sharps are consistent with epileptogenicity at T3 that places this patient at high risk of localization-related epilepsy.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 64-year-old gentleman with history of hypertension, alcoholic cirrhosis, stroke presents with seizures.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, valproic acid, and others.
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab using standard international 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to 1 channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was not performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness through drowsiness.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 6.5 to 7 Hz well formed on the right side in the occipital region, which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity.  The background activity is characterized by diffuse slowing consisting of 5-6 Hz theta activity intermixed with 3 to 3.5 Hz delta activity.  There is intermittent left posterior quadrant slowing in theta and delta frequencies with loss of faster frequencies and attenuation.  This activity was associated with occasional spikes and spike-and-wave complexes with no evolution.  There were also triphasic waves seen intermittently with an anterior-posterior gradient with a frequency of 1.5 Hz, occasionally well formed on the right side.  The background is intermixed with periodic lateralized epileptiform discharges seen in the left posterior quadrant lasting for 1 to 1-1/2 minute with no evolution or behavioral changes.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient in a wakefulness and drowsiness due to,
Disorganized and slow background activity in theta and delta range.
Left posterior quadrant slowing with loss of faster frequencies and attenuations.
Left posterior quadrant occasional spikes and spike-and-wave complexes with no evolutions.
Presence of triphasic waves.
Left posterior quadrant PLEDs maximal at T5 with no behavioral changes or evolutions.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The diffuse slowing and triphasic waves are suggestive of either metabolic, toxic, anoxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunctions.  Left focal slowing with loss of faster frequencies and attenuation is consistent with a history of left MCA stroke. Occasional spikes in left posterior region are suggestive of underlying epileptogenicity. PLEDs suggest underlying cortical irritability due to an underlying structural lesion such as stroke, tumor, or infection predisposing to epileptic seizures. These PLEDs did not evolve in seizures. This does not rule out intermittent seizures.  Clinical correlation is recommended.

MEDICATIONS:  Include Lamictal and prenatal vitamins.
INTRODUCTION:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system of with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed, since the patient is 8 months' pregnant.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of a well-formed and modulated 11.5-12 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eye opening.  There is an anterior-to-posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies of low amplitude anteriorly.  During sleep, symmetrical vertex wave and sleep spindles are captured.  Intermittent frequently arrhythmic beta activity is captured over the left posterior quadrant.  Additionally, intermittent low to moderate amplitude sharp waves with after-going slow waves are observed over the left posterior quadrant, with phase reversal over T5, O1, P3, C3 electrodes.  Frequency of these discharges increases during sleep.  At times, they are imbedded within the rhythmic alpha range monomorphic activity.  On a single occasion, at approximately 3:01:50 p.m., a rhythmic burst in alpha range is noted over the left anterior temporal/frontal region.
FINDINGS:
Frequent left posterior quadrant/occipital sharp waves with after-going slow waves.
Intermittent mild, at times rhythmic, focal left posterior quadrant slowing.
Stage 2 sleep.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal awake and asleep 26-minute EEG due to intermittent left posterior quadrant sharp waves with after-going slow waves as well as left posterior quadrant mild focal slowing that at times is rhythmic.  These findings indicate focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and is suggestive of focal mechanism of seizures.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 65-year-old man with a history of a MCA stroke and seizures, as well as liver failure who now presents with a change in mental status.
MEDICATIONS:  Potassium, propranolol, rifaximin, lisinopril, Lasix, Protonix, Lovenox, aspirin, Thiamine, Keppra, Zonisamide, spironolactone, and risperidone.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single lead EKG lead.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Photic stimulation was performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  There is no clear posterior dominant rhythm and no anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient.  The background consists of a mixture of polymorphic theta and delta.  Additional moderate amplitude frontally predominant intermittent rhythmic delta activity (FIRDA) is observed.  During sleep the degree of slowing increases, occasionally.  The discontinuity is observed, and the sleep spindles are noted.  There is paucity of faster frequencies over the left hemisphere.  Four seizures were observed.  The seizures occurred at 12:23:01 p.m., 12:26 p.m., 12:45:18 p.m., and 12:48:23 p.m.  The longest seizure duration was approximately 80 seconds.  The seizures start with lower amplitude fast activity over the left  occipital region.  This activity rapidly increases in amplitude and becomes more sharply contoured and rhythmic.  As seizure evolves additional rhythmic sharply contoured delta activity is observed over the left frontal central region with significant reflection over the rest of the brain.  As the seizure progresses left occipital activity decreases in frequency and increases in amplitude.  Clinically, the patient is unable to answer questions or follow commands during the seizure.  He repeatedly repeats the word "yeah" when asked to follow commands or answer questions.  Hyperventilation was not performed.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in additional abnormalities.
FINDINGS:
Moderate diffuse slowing.
Moderate focal left hemispheric slowing.
Electrographic seizures, left occipital onset, up to 80 seconds in duration, occurring in clusters of 2.
FIRDA.
IMPRESSION:  This is a very abnormal 42 minute EEG due to moderate diffuse slowing that is more pronounced over the left hemisphere, and 4 focal electrographic seizures of left occipital onset.  Diffuse slowing indicates etiologically nonspecific diffuse cerebral dysfunction.  Focal left hemispheric slowing and focal left occipital onset seizures indicate focal cerebral dysfunction, likely structural in etiology, and is consistent with the patient's history of a left hemispheric stroke.  FIRDA could be seen in encephalopathy, increased intracranial pressure and white matter lesions.  These findings were conveyed to the Neurology Team at the time of the review.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizure.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 59-year-old man with a history of alcohol abuse, multiple lacunar infarcts, chronic small-vessel disease, noncompliant on medications, comes with a chief complaint of status epilepticus.
TECHNICAL:  Difficulties none.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using the standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness and sleep.  Activating procedures were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a diffusely slow background with a posterior dominant rhythm that at best reaches 6 Hz which appears to be somewhat reactive to eye opening.  There is some frontocentral beta during wakefulness.  Activating procedures were not performed.  The patient is recorded during wakefulness and sleep and easily goes into sleep.  During the recording, specifically as the patient goes to sleep, there appears to be small sharply contoured discharges seen at T3 and at T4 most consistent with benign epileptiform transient of sleep.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  Mild generalized slowing at 5-7 Hz seen continuously during withdrawal wakefulness throughout the recording.
SEIZURES:
None.
HEART RATE:  102.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to mild generalized slowing.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG reveals evidence of diffuse cerebral dysfunction, which is nonspecific with regards to etiology.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  Again please note that benign epileptiform  sharp transients (BETS) were seen in this recording.

REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 60-year-old woman with a past medical history of an AVM, status post surgeries and strokes with seizures.  She has been seizure free for years, but has had some intermittent feelings of off balance within the month of June.
MEDICATIONS:  Trileptal.
INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 system with additional anterior temporal and single lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a posterior dominant rhythm that is best seen over the left hemisphere and reaches 9 Hz.  There is normal frontal central beta seen over the left hemisphere only.  Over the right hemisphere the posterior dominant rhythm is disrupted and the frontal central beta is accentuated and a large area of amplitude consistent with a breach, which I will describe in the abnormal discharges.
Abnormal discharges:
Focal sharp waves seen frequently at F8/T4 and independently at T4 in wakefulness and sleep.
Focal sharp waves seen also at F7/T3 and at T3, but only occasionally.  These are also seen in wakefulness and sleep.
Continuous focal slowing seen over T4 at a frequency of 2-4 Hz at an amplitude of 20-60 mV with an associated increasing faster frequency in amplitude consistent with a breach rhythm.
Seizures:  None.
Heart rate:  66.
IMPRESSION:  Abnormal EEG due to independent right anterior temporal and mid temporal sharp waves, as well as left mid temporal and anterior temporal sharp waves.  In addition, there is evidence of focal structural dysfunction and irritability over the right mid temporal region which is consistent with a known AVM and surgery.  No seizures were seen.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old woman who presents with change in mental status.  She had left arm and leg twitching.
PAST MEDICAL HISTORY:  Significant for coronary artery disease, hypertension, diabetes, COPD.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra, morphine, Seroquel and valproic acid.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed at the bedside using standard 10/20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation or photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  No clear posterior dominant rhythm was seen.  In the lethargic state there was diffuse slowing of the background consisting of 5-6 Hz theta activity intermixed with 2-3 Hz delta activity.  These activities are intermixed with occasional beta activity with frontocentral distribution.  There was occasional eye movement artifact noted.  There is a spontaneous variability seen with increase in background frequency intermittently.  There is also some reactivity seen in the form of increased background frequency on stimulating the patient.  There is no epileptiform abnormality or electrographic seizures during this recording.  Heart rate is 100 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording capturing the patient in a lethargic state due to the presence of: 1. Diffuse slowing of the background.  2. Absence of posterior dominant rhythm. There is no epileptiform activity or electrographic seizures noted.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above findings could be due to severe metabolic, toxic, anoxic, or infectious encephalopathy or a postictal state.  Alternatively, it could also be due to the effects of sedating medications.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures were captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.  Please note, the patient is tachycardic.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 74-year-old gentleman with history of epilepsy known for the last 6 years, who presents for followup.  He has been seizure-free for a while.
MEDICATIONS:  Carbatrol, Neurontin, Lopressor, metformin, omeprazole, atorvastatin, hydrochlorothiazide, metoprolol, aspirin.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation was performed.  This was an awake and drowsy record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the posterior dominant rhythm was 7-7.5 Hz in frequency seen in the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontal central beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  Drowsiness is characterized by disappearance of the posterior dominant rhythm and slowing of the background, and absence of muscle and eye blink artifact.  There is 6-7 Hz diffuse theta activity seen during wakefulness, which is distributed symmetrically.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and results in no driving response.  Heart rate was 60 beats per minute and regular.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG recording due to:
Diffuse slowing of the background with theta activity seen in wakefulness.
Slowing of the posterior dominant rhythm.
There is no epileptiform activity or electrographic seizures noted during this recording.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The above finding could be due to metabolic, toxic, or infectious encephalopathy.  Alternatively, it could be due to the effect of sedating medications or bilateral cerebral dysfunction or degenerative brain disease.  Clinical correlation is recommended.  No epileptiform abnormalities are identified in this record.  No seizures are captured.  This does not rule out the diagnosis of epilepsy or intermittent seizures.  If clinically indicated, a repeat EEG capturing deeper stages of sleep or continuous bedside EEG monitoring may be helpful.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This 41-year-old woman has refractory epilepsy, status post right temporal lobectomy with ongoing seizures characterized by no aura,  foaming at the mouth, impairment of awareness.
MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin, Haldol, Cogentin, Claritin and others.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Impedances were satisfactory, aside from T1, T2. The patient had a previous craniotomy.  This is a routine 26-minute EEG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is poorly organized.  A posterior dominant rhythm of 10 hertz is noted bilaterally.  It is higher amplitude on the left compared to the right.  A rhythmic delta is noted in either temporal region, right more so than the left.  Despite the breech rhythm, sharp waves were noted in the right central temporal region.  In addition, there are occasional sharp waves noted in pairs on the left.
Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background. At the close of hyperventilation, as the patient becomes drowsy, additional sharp waves are noted, more so in the left temporal region than the right.  In sleep, with an increase in background beta, epileptiform activity is seen from the right anterior temporal region.  Occasional bursts of shifting slowing, including the posterior temporal regions or posterior regions, was also identified.
Photic stimulation elicited a bilateral driving response.  In addition, the patient was starting to transition into stage 2 sleep during photic stimulation.  Right anterior temporal polyspike activity was noted in that transition to stage 2 sleep.
Heart rate:  66 BPM.
IMPRESSION:  This is an abnormal EEG due to:
Background slowing and disorganization.
Independent, right or left temporal sharp waves, some of which are anterior temporal, occasionally with a more posterior temporal region.
Right temporal poly spikes noted in sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  The background slowing and disorganization suggest a bihemispheric process.  Right temporal focal slowing is anticipated following a temporal lobectomy.  This patient has persistent epileptiform activity seen from both hemispheres, suggesting more than one localization site for her epilepsy.
